<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aid for Hurricane Victims Stranded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Six months after Hurricane Mitch tore through  
Central America, tons of donated relief supplies are still stranded 
in New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	At least two warehouses are stuffed with clothes, food, bottled  
water and medical supplies stacked on pallets and ready to be sent 
to Honduras and Nicaragua. Some medicine is now outdated and must 
be thrown away. 
</P>
<P>
	In the rush to gather goods to help the hurricane's victims in  
Central America, insurmountable transportation problems emerged, 
relief groups say. 
</P>
<P>
	One group had to delay shipments for several months to a key  
Honduran port inundated with thousands of shipping containers full 
of relief supplies. Another group's shipments were stalled when the 
promise of a boat to transport the goods to Nicaragua fell through. 
</P>
<P>
	For people involved in the relief efforts, the wait has been  
frustrating. Dr. Mayer Heiman's voice broke as he stood in a 
warehouse near boxes of canned food and bottled baby food and said 
his group had reports of children starving in a remote part of 
Honduras. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would send all this down tomorrow if we could,'' said  
Heiman, president of the International Hospital for Children in New 
Orleans and a chief organizer of its relief effort. ``We've been 
waiting months to get all of this out of here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital received tons of donations by late December. Dole  
Fresh Fruit and Chiquita Brands International were shipping 
containers to Honduras for free. But organizers had to halt 
shipments in January when Honduran officials stopped accepting 
containers sent to the country's major port, Puerto Cortez. 
</P>
<P>
	Even after the port reopened, organizers were reluctant to  
resume shipments to Honduras. In the interim, they'd learned 
supplies were most sorely needed in some of Central America's 
remotest spots, and the hurricane had destroyed roads, sending 
trucking costs skyhigh. They had no assurances the donations would 
get through. 
</P>
<P>
	Heiman said his group's members wanted to send food, medicine  
and hospital supplies to the Miskito Indians who live in a swampy 
and impoverished area accessible only by boat. But they couldn't 
find a boat that could carry large amounts while navigating the 
shallow water. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting things shipped to where we want them has been the  
problem,'' Heiman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments resumed in April, and Heiman said his group will use a  
Roman Catholic church boat to send food, medicine and seeds for 
planting crops to the Miskitos. But the hospital's warehouse 
probably won't be emptied until June. 
</P>
<P>
	Another New Orleans group, the Nicaraguan Independent Committee  
for Assistance, arranged free shipment of relief supplies to 
Nicaragua in December on a cargo ship. The ship's owner planned to 
pay for the trip by bringing cargo from Nicaragua back to the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	But the offer was rescinded when no goods materialized for the  
return trip, said Dr. Christian Mayorga, chairman of the group. 
</P>
<P>
	When Puerto Cortez got jammed up, blocking efforts to get  
supplies overland from Honduras to Nicaragua, some of the group's 
supplies were sent to Nicaragua on Louisiana National Guard planes, 
but much more languished in two warehouses. In April, thieves were 
arrested after they broke into one of the warehouses and stole 
supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayorga's group is now sending two 40-foot containers a week to  
Honduras, each carrying 60,000 pounds of supplies. From Honduras, 
the goods are trucked to Nicaragua. All of the group's donations 
should be in the country by June. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our people are still in great need, and we are going to  
continue this task,'' Mayorga said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the lesson is that logistical problems can overwhelm  
humanitarian efforts. It was easy to gather the donations, mostly 
from Louisiana residents, because New Orleans has a large 
population of people with Central American roots. But getting the 
goods to Central America rapidly proved difficult, then virtually 
impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, the circumstances were very adverse,'' Mayorga  
said. ``We did not know how big this enterprise was going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another solution to send supplies directly to remote coastal  
areas of Honduras should be ready in a few days. Sub Ocean Safety, 
a nonprofit group, is refurbishing a World War II beach landing 
craft for regular trips and expects to make its maiden voyage to 
Honduras on May 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Sub Ocean Safety plans to take 100 tons of food, construction  
materials and hand tools to hard-hit parts of the country, said 
Robert Izdepski, the group's president. 
</P>
<P>
	The landing craft -- large enough to hold three military tanks --  
will shuttle supplies along the Honduran coast for other relief 
groups before returning to New Orleans to pick up more donated 
goods. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still a lot of stuff here and there's still a lot of  
need,'' Izdepski said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
