<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How IRS' Tax Return Pipeline Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Each of the 10 IRS Service Centers operates what is called ``The  
Pipeline'' to process the tens of millions of paper tax returns 
mailed each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's how it works:  
</P>
<P>
	-- During peak filing season, thousands of tax returns are  
trucked to the service center every day. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Mail is opened manually and sorted by type of return into  
slots at wooden ``Tingle'' tables, named for an employee who 
invented them. Checks are immediately set aside and deposited that 
day in a federal reserve bank. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Returns are hand-stamped with a 13-number code.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Employees examine returns for common errors, circling key  
information by hand and checking that all taxpayer information is 
included. Returns that appear questionable go into the ``funny 
box'' for further investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Data from each return is entered by hand, processed by a local  
mainframe computer and then sent to the tape Master File located in 
Martinsburg, W.Va. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
