<HEADLINE> Olerud On-Base Streak Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- John Olerud's streak of reaching base safely in  
consecutive games ended at 47 today when he struck out as a pinch 
hitter for the final out of the New York Mets' 11-6 loss to the 
Arizona Diamondbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Olerud was the only pinch-hit option left in the  
dugout for the Mets, who carry 12 pitchers and 13 position players 
on their roster. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just one of those things that had to end sooner or  
later,'' he said. ``I'll just try to get another streak started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olerud had reached base either with a hit or a walk in the last  
17 games of last year and the first 30 this years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was not anything I paid a whole lot of attention to,'' he  
said. ``Every time you go to the plate, you just try to put 
pressure on the pitcher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olerud's streak ended three games short of the Mets'  
single-season record of 33 set by Darryl Strawberry in 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
