<DOCNO> APW19990509.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 09:51:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Helped Atlanta Get Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Former President George Bush was among several  
high-ranking government officials who helped Atlanta secure the 
1996 Olympics, according to records released by bid organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush videotaped a two-minute message that Atlanta organizers  
presented to the International Olympic Committee during its final 
bid presentation in September, 1990 in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush sent personal letters to each IOC member just before the  
final vote, according to documents in nine boxes of Olympic records 
released by the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation. A bid team 
memo said Bush's message was ``very effective,'' The Atlanta 
Journal-Constitution reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta beat out Athens, Toronto and Birmingham, England, for  
the right to host the 1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The records show the Atlanta organizers also enlisted the help  
of the U.S. State Department, then-U.S. Sen. Sam Nunn and then-Vice 
President Dan Quayle. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine boxes are a fraction of 4,000 boxes of Olympic  
documents kept by the athletics foundation, which Payne founded to 
spearhead Atlanta's bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper and the foundation are locked in a legal battle  
over the release of the rest of the records. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper says it wants to see if the records contain  
evidence of corruption like that uncovered in Salt Lake City's 
successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. House subcommittee investigating the Salt Lake scandal is  
already investigating the files, looking for the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletics foundation claims the documents are the property  
of a group of private citizens, and therefore are not governed by 
the state's Open Records Act. State Attorney General Thurbert Baker 
has declared they are open, prompting the foundation to file suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Roy Barnes has also said he believes the records should be  
open to the public, as the Games involved massive amounts of public 
funding for transportation and security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 09:41:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Votes Gore, Bradley Split On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some votes that split Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley during  
their years in the Senate: 

</P>
<P>
	 *AIDS:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Require states to have laws requiring good-faith effort to  
notify spouses of those infected with HIV (1989) 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley yes, Gore no  

</P>
<P>
	 *ECONOMY:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Approve Gramm-Rudman-Hollings law establishing ceilings on the  
federal deficit (1985) 
</P>
<P>
	Gore yes, Bradley no  
</P>
<P>
	-- Approve a balanced budget amendment to the U.S. Constitution  
(1986) 
</P>
<P>
	Gore yes, Bradley no  
</P>
<P>
	-- Approve trade bill cutting down on textile and shoe imports  
from several foreign countries (1985) 
</P>
<P>
	Gore yes, Bradley no  

</P>
<P>
	 *DEATH PENALTY:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Authorize death penalty for drug kingpins or heads of  
continuing criminal enterprise (1990) 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley yes, Gore no  

</P>
<P>
	 *EDUCATION:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Create school choice demonstration project to help low-income  
parents send their children to public, private or religious schools 
(1992) 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley yes, Gore no  

</P>
<P>
	 *ENVIRONMENT:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Keep 1.2 million acres of Montana wilderness off limits to  
development (1992) 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley yes, Gore no  

</P>
<P>
	 *IMMIGRATION:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Overhaul immigration laws to penalize employers that hire  
undocumented workers and to create a ``guest worker'' program 
allowing foreign workers into the United States for up to nine 
months for agricultural work (1985) 
</P>
<P>
	Gore yes, Bradley no  

</P>
<P>
	 *MILITARY AND FOREIGN AFFAIRS:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Authorize use of military force against Iraq (1991)  
</P>
<P>
	Gore yes, Bradley no  
</P>
<P>
	-- Provide $100 million in aid to Contra guerilla forces in  
Nicaragua (1986) 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley yes, Gore no  

</P>
<P>
	 *NASA:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Transfer $118 million from NASA funding for space station to  
veterans administration for health care (1987) 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley yes, Gore no  

</P>
<P>
	 *TOBACCO:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Help the tobacco industry by letting manufacturers buy 1.2  
billion pounds of surplus tobacco, much of it from the government, 
at deep discounts (1985) 
</P>
<P>
	Gore yes, Bradley no  

</P>
<P>
	 *WELFARE:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Require all states to provide welfare benefits to poor  
two-parent families and requiring at least one parent to enroll in 
first workfare program (1988) 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley yes, Gore no  

</P>
<P>
	Source: Congressional Quarterly  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
