<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 18:21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Week Wasn't Grand for Maddux </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- On Tuesday, Greg Maddux allowed just the second  
grand slam of his career -- to Mark McGwire, no less. 
</P>
<P>
	By Sunday, his ERA was up to an un-Madduxlike 4.57.  
</P>
<P>
	After allowing 10 hits in six innings of Sunday's 5-0 loss to  
the San Diego Padres, the Atlanta Braves right-hander said he 
doesn't think he's pitching that badly. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's the kind of day he had: He allowed a three-run homer by  
John Vander Wal to center field, but kept his chief nemesis, 
eight-time batting champion Tony Gwynn, from hitting one out of the 
infield. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other guy (Sterling Hitchcock) threw a good game,'' said  
Maddux (4-2), who last year claimed his fourth NL ERA title with a 
2.22 mark. ``I'm upset about the homer I gave up. I didn't get hit 
hard with the exception of Vander Wal. (Jim) Leyritz hit a ball 
good up the middle and Reggie (Sanders) hit a ball good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vander Wal said the changeup he hit out in the sixth ``didn't  
have the life on it that he wanted, the sharp downward tilt that he 
normally gets with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just the luck of the draw that he left a pitch up and I  
got ahold of it,'' said Vander Wal, whose homer cleared the fence 
just to the right of straightaway center. ``I knew at least I had a 
sac fly, and I was fortunate enough it went out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quilvio Veras, struggling along at .169, hit a two-run single to  
break a scoreless tie in the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there was Gwynn, who turned 39 on Sunday but got no gifts  
from Maddux. Gwynn has more hits off Maddux -- 35 -- than he has off 
any other pitcher, but went 0-for-3 to see his career average 
against him dip from .455 to .438 (35-for-80). 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hitting .450 against him?'' Gwynn said. ``So I'm supposed  
to get a hit against him every time? Shoot, he's still hard to 
hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn said Maddux was locating his pitches where he wanted them.  
</P>
<P>
	``First time up he throws me four changeups. Next time he comes  
with a big sweeping curve, which he hardly ever throws. Then he 
busts me on the knuckles with a heater. You can't sit on anything. 
You're just trying to put the bat on the ball,'' Gwynn said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never feel comfortable because he can do so many things,  
either with his movement or his location.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
