<DOCNO> APW19990509.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 16:12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Webber, Kings Vow To Work Harder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Chris Webber spent two weeks resting his  
aching back -- for this? 
</P>
<P>
	The Sacramento Kings' star forward has been to the playoffs  
three times with three teams, but has yet to win a postseason game. 
He fell to 0-7 with the Kings' 117-87 thrashing courtesy of the 
Utah Jazz on Saturday, the worst playoff loss in the franchise's 
51-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	Webber, Sacramento's leading scorer and rebounder, got into  
early foul trouble and wasn't a factor as the Jazz cruised to a 
23-point first-half lead. After missing five critical late-season 
games while resting a sprained joint in his back, Webber didn't 
enjoy getting crowned in his Kings postseason debut. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't even know how frustrating that was,'' Webber said.  
``I wanted to help us out more, but you can't make a difference 
when you're not on the court. I think I just have to work harder at 
every part of my game, and I have to play smarter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So do his teammates. While the Jazz held a light workout at  
their West Valley City practice gym and went home early, the Kings 
sweated through more than three hours of practice and a fil, 
session Sunday at the Delta Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, we needed it,'' Webber said. ``This team isn't going to  
give up just because things went wrong in Game 1. There's still a 
lot of basketball left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game 2 in the best-of-5 round is Monday night, and the series  
shifts to Arco Arena in Sacramento for Game 3 Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings swept into the postseason as one of the league's  
hottest teams, with 10 wins in their last 11 games. But the Jazz, 
playing in their 16th consecutive postseason, showed a poise and 
game-readiness that can only be learned through years of experience 
-- something Sacramento doesn't have. 
</P>
<P>
	``They showed us how to come out and be ready to play,''  
Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said. ``The playoffs are a totally 
different game, and we're a young team. We learned a lot 
(Saturday).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adelman broke down the Kings' loss on film and highlighted  
breakdowns on fast breaks, on defense and in their half-court 
offense -- ``Basically, everything,'' Webber laughed. 
</P>
<P>
	``You always look worse on film, so it was even worse than the  
game, if you can imagine that,'' Jon Barry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Webber picked up two fouls less than six minutes into the first  
quarter. The Kings already were down 19-8, and with Webber on the 
bench, Karl Malone and the Jazz made a 10-4 run that essentially 
buried Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	Webber came back in the second quarter but missed three shots  
and was hit with his third foul. He didn't score until a minute 
remained in the half, and 10 of his 14 points came after Utah had 
an insurmountable second-half lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just have to take your punches and get back up,'' Webber  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	After a lockout-lengthened offseason of uncertainty during which  
he publicly aired his dismay over being traded from Washington to 
Sacramento, Webber had a stellar first season with the Kings. He 
won his first league rebounding title and led the Kings to the same 
number of wins (27) in a 50-game schedule as they managed during 
the 82-game 1997-98 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	But his playing time and effectiveness were curtailed late in  
the year by his back injury, and though he said he is more than 
healthy enough to play, ``at times, it definitely is a little 
stiff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Webber on the bench in foul trouble, the Kings had no  
answer for Malone, who scored 21 points in the game's first three 
quarters, and Utah's balanced attack. Six Jazz players finished in 
double figures, while Utah held Sacramento to 36.5 percent shooting 
and outrebounded the Kings 48-38. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Jerry Sloan wasn't entirely pleased.  
</P>
<P>
	``We still haven't played 48 minutes of defense this season,''  
the Jazz coach said. ``I was happy we came out intensely on 
offense, but we let them do a number of things on offense that 
could come back to haunt us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After posting his lowest scoring average in a decade during the  
regular season, Jeff Hornacek was back in the swing of things 
Saturday. He scored 18 points on 8-of-11 shooting and added seven 
assists, all against defensive specialist Tariq Abdul-Wahad. 
</P>
<P>
	``We recognize that that's just one game,'' Hornacek said. ``We  
don't ever think beyond the next game, but we also know from 
experience that you can't take too much from one bad performance.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 12:32:12 </DATE_TIME>
