<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 23:23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Critics Target the TEC-9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As two high school gunmen fired on their  
classmates in Littleton, Colo., Dennis Henigan was honing his 
arguments in a lawsuit against the maker of the pistol used in 
their assault. 
</P>
<P>
	His case is the latest in a spate of largely unsuccessful  
efforts to hold Miami-based Navegar responsible for killings 
committed with the TEC-9, a 9 mm semiautomatic handgun. 
</P>
<P>
	The TEC-9 is well known to authorities. Federal agents say it is  
more likely to be used in a crime than any other handgun although 
it's been banned by federal and state governments. 
</P>
<P>
	And while the TEC-9, and spinoffs like the TEC DC-9, have a poor  
reputation among gun sellers, police say drug dealers prefer them 
because they're cheap, can carry 36-bullet clips and, at 12.5 
inches, are easily concealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Henigan, a lawyer for the Washington, D.C.-based Center to  
Prevent Handgun Violence, sued on behalf of victims of a massacre 
at a San Francisco office building. 
</P>
<P>
	In July 1993, Gian Luigi Ferri, a mentally disturbed man with a  
grudge against lawyers, used a TEC DC-9 to kill eight people and 
wound six others in a law office, then killed himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the gun is so small, Ferri was able to tote his weapon  
and 250 rounds of ammunition in his briefcase undetected. Like 
other semiautomatics, TEC-9 style guns automatically reload a 
bullet into the chamber, allowing a gunman to fire as fast as he 
can pull the trigger. 
</P>
<P>
	``The TEC-9 a particular favorite among criminal offenders,''  
said James Alan Fox, dean of the College of Criminal Justice at 
Northeastern University in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The more violent the crime, the greater the chance a TEC-9 is  
used, Fox found in a study of 1991-1994 data, making the gun 
``especially a weapon of choice among violent offenders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gun, found under the brand name Intratec, is among the 10  
firearms that make it fastest from the original dealer to a crime, 
according to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	Henigan says the problem isn't simply that criminals favor the  
TEC-9 -- it's that Navegar has gone out of its way to market the gun 
to criminals. Ads called the TEC-9 ``tough as your toughest 
customer,'' and said it has a finish with ``excellent resistance to 
fingerprints.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whenever the gun has been banned, Navegar made modest changes to  
the TEC-9, renamed it and then produced a legal version. 
</P>
<P>
	After the District of Columbia banned the gun by name in 1991,  
Navegar eliminated threads on the barrel that could accommodate a 
silencer and changed the name to TEC DC-9. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very clear that this company has made a determined effort  
to try to evade statutes designed to restrict the sale of its 
assault weapons,'' Henigan said. 
</P>
<P>
	When the TEC-9 and DC-9 were listed in the 1994 federal assault  
weapons ban, Navegar came out with the AB-10. Critics say the 
letters stand for ``after ban.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's essentially no functional difference to them,'' said  
Bob Glass, a gun shop owner and publisher of libertarian magazine 
``The Partisan,'' based in Longmont, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Reached at his Coral Gables, Fla., home, Navegar owner Carlos  
Garcia declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Although assault bans have outlawed manufacture of the gun, they  
do not ban the sale of pre-ban guns. That's the reason there are an 
estimated 100,000 TEC-9, TEC DC-9 and AB-10 handguns in American 
homes. 
</P>
<P>
	One appealing aspect to the TEC-9 series is its price -- cheap.  
</P>
<P>
	A banned Uzi pistol costs about $1,400, and Heckler and Koch  
makes a banned SP-89 that costs $3,000. A post-ban semiautomatic 
made by Professional Ordinance retails for more than $1,200. 
</P>
<P>
	But the post-ban AB-10 sells at retail gun shops for $225 to  
$275. Federal and state bans have driven up the price of pre-ban 
TEC-9 guns to only about $350. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, gun dealers say TEC-9 guns are inaccurate and prone to  
jam. Investigators in Littleton say the large number of unused 
bullets at the scene suggests the TEC DC-9 used by Dylan Klebold 
may have jammed. 
</P>
<P>
	``You wouldn't see any professional criminals using it, people  
who know what they're doing,'' Glass said. ``If you're going to rob 
a bank you want your gun to work. If you're a 15-year-old crackhead 
who wants to steal a car, that's different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the last five years, Navegar has been sued in at least four  
cases in Florida, one in Arizona, two in Illinois and one in 
Louisiana. Those cases are pending. 
</P>
<P>
	For those like Henigan who seek to hold Navegar responsible for  
the deeds done with its weapons, it's an uphill struggle. Henigan's 
case has already been thrown out of court once and is now scheduled 
to be heard on appeal in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
