<HEADLINE> Baffert's Plans Call for 2 Fillies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Trainer Bob Baffert's latest lineup for  
Saturday's $1 million Preakness now includes star fillies 
Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting and excludes Prime Timber. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert says Prime Timber, fourth in the Kentucky Derby, is  
definitely out of the Preakness and will run instead in the Sir 
Barton Stakes on Saturday's undercard. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, the plan is to run both fillies in the Preakness,''  
Baffert said Saturday, before he sent out Real Quiet -- last year's 
Derby-Preakness winner -- to victory in the Pimlico Special. ``Both 
fillies will be entered in the Black-Eyed Susan (on Friday) and the 
Preakness in case the draw for the Preakness is unfavorable. I'm 
leaving my options open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three horses were scheduled for workouts either Monday or  
Tuesday at Churchill Downs before shipping to Pimlico on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, a winner in 10 of 11 career starts, has never  
run against males. In her last race, she won the Kentucky Oaks on 
April 30 at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting tested males for the first time in the Derby,  
finishing a strong fifth -- just over 2 1/2 lengths behind the winner 
Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	``They deserve a chance,'' Baffert said of his fillies.  
``Excellent Meeting showed it in the Derby. She had probably the 
worst trip of any horse in the race. She could have easily won. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silverbulletday had a very easy race in the Kentucky Oaks. You  
hate to run them against each other, but it's going to be a great 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If both run, it would mark the first time since 1921 that more  
than one filly has run in the Preakness. Four fillies have won, but 
none since Nellie Morse in 1924. Rhine Maiden won in 1915, 
Whimsical in 1906 and Flocarline in 1903. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Prime Timber, Baffert said: ``If I'm going to the Belmont  
with him, I can't just sit on him. He has to run to get ready to go 
a mile and a half.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Belmont Stakes is June 5.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DERBY WINNER DOING FINE:* Charismatic, the surprise Derby  
winner at odds of 31-1, and third-place finisher Cat Thief, 
galloped Sunday at Churchill Downs and will have their final 
workouts on Tuesday before shipping to Pimlico. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're doing great,'' said Mark Maker, trainer D. Wayne  
Lukas' assistant. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PREAKNESS PRATTLE:* K One King, eighth in the Derby, is out of  
the Preakness with a small chip on his left front ankle. ... Badge, 
winner of the Gotham Stakes, was scheduled for a final workout 
Monday at Belmont Park before trainer Joe Aquilino decides whether 
to ship his colt to Pimlico. ... Kimberlite Pipe, sixth in the 
Derby, will be ridden by Shane Sellers in the Preakness. Sellers 
rode Vicar to an 18th-place finish in the Derby. ... Trainer Nick 
Zito says Adonis and Stephen Got Even will have their final 
Preakness workouts on Tuesday at Pimlico. ... Derby runner-up 
Menifee was scheduled to work Monday at Churchill Downs before 
Wednesday's trip to Baltimore. ``Everything is good so far,'' 
trainer Elliott Walden said. ... If Valhol is unable to run in the 
Preakness due to insufficient earnings, trainer Dallas Keen says 
the gelding will start in the Sir Barton Stakes. ... Vicar, 18th in 
the Derby, was scheduled to work Tuesday at Churchill Downs before 
trainer Carl Nafzger makes a final decision on whether to run him 
in the Preakness. 
</P>
