<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Girl Walks in Justice's Shoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) -- Seventh-grader Rebecca DenHartigh is  
walking in Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor's shoes. No, 
not following in her footsteps. She's really wearing her shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebecca is one of 25 students in Cindy Broekhuizen's  
seventh-grade language arts class at East Christian School who were 
assigned to choose a role model, write a research paper about the 
person and send the paper to them along with a request for a pair 
of their shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping this would give the students the opportunity to  
walk in someone's shoes and imagine what it would be like to be 
that person,'' Ms. Broekhuizen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks after Rebecca sent her letter to O'Connor, a Federal  
Express package arrived with a pair of size 8 1/2, light green, 
black-tipped, rubber-soled shoes once worn by the nation's first 
female Supreme Court justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebecca wore them the rest of the day.  
</P>
<P>
	``They fit perfectly,'' she told the Kalamazoo Gazette. ``I feel  
proud knowing that a person of such great importance would give me 
a pair of her shoes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only one other role model sent footwear: trumpeter Wynton  
Marsalis, who shipped a pair of size 9 shoes to William Karsten. 
Unlike Rebecca, William couldn't wear his new shoes-- his feet are 
size 14. 
</P>
<P>
	The shoes are staying at the school for a display.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
