<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jenny Jones Defends Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Despite a $25 million verdict against her talk  
show, Jenny Jones said in an interview that the program is not to 
blame for the shooting death of a guest who revealed a gay crush on 
another guest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course I did soul searching. Of course after this happened  
we went back. I thought back about the show and we all, you know, 
we all talked about it. We then and now still feel we did nothing 
wrong,'' Ms. Jones told ``Dateline NBC'' interviewer Jane Pauley in 
an interview broadcast Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's not fair to blame the show for the actions of  
someone. That happened three days after they left the show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A jury last week held the show and its corporate owner, Warner  
Bros., liable in the shooting death of Scott Amedure, who had 
revealed his attraction to Jonathan Schmitz during a 1995 taping of 
the program. Amedure was shot dead three days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones said she might feel guilty if the two had been  
introduced on the show, but they had met beforehand. 
</P>
<P>
	The First Amendment protects the right of ``The Jenny Jones  
Show'' to offer segments like the one about same-sex secret 
crushes, Ms. Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said that compared to other shows, her program is ``probably  
the most lighthearted, fun show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amedure, 32, and Schmitz, then 24, were in Chicago on March 6,  
1995, to tape a segment for ``The Jenny Jones Show'' about secret 
crushes. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz, expecting to meet a woman, was kept offstage while  
Amedure declared his attraction to him and described a sexual 
fantasy involving Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Three days later, Schmitz bought a shotgun and shells, drove to  
Amedure's mobile home and shot him to death. His 1996 conviction on 
second-degree murder charges was thrown out on a technicality. His 
retrial is set for this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The segment never aired.  
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Amedure's family argued that the show ``lit the  
fuse'' leading to his death by first deceiving, then embarrassing 
an already disturbed Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones said the show made it clear to Schmitz that his  
admirer could be a man or woman, and that it had no way of knowing 
about Schmitz's suicide attempts or struggles against alcoholism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 22:23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ball Field Upsets Neighbors in N.J. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Bill Ingraham was weaned on baseball,  
playing pickup games with his friends in the neighborhood every 
summer since he was 4 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Wanting to pass along his love the game to his son, Ingraham set  
about constructing a major-league-size field on his property, 
complete with batting cages and an indoor gymnasium. 
</P>
<P>
	Now his neighbors are crying foul.  
</P>
<P>
	Tewksbury Township officials say Ingraham turned their quiet  
corner of horse country into something like Yankee Stadium -- with 
12-hour days filled with the pinging of aluminum bats, spectators' 
cheers and whistles. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a free-for-all back here,'' said Kathy DeSerio, whose  
yard borders Ingraham's left field. ``I like the Yankees. I don't 
know if I want the Yankees back in my back yard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of Ingraham's baseball diamond plan to go to court  
today in Flemington to argue that his $300,000 field of dreams 
violates township zoning laws and is a public nuisance. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingraham said he pays $1,500 a month to maintain the field for  
his 11-year-old son, Brian, and his son's friends. He goes to work 
every morning by 4 a.m. so he can leave by 2 p.m., in time to play 
on the field with the kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son enjoys it,'' Ingraham said. ``That's our thing.''  
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer, Terrence Scott, has argued that the field, which  
Ingraham never got a permit to build, should be considered an 
accessory to his property, much like a swimming pool or tennis 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	People in Tewksbury, a township of 5,000 with a median income of  
$98,000, wouldn't be as angry if Ingraham was indulging in the 
area's more popular sports of horseback riding or tennis, Scott 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Township attorney James Knox said the field itself isn't a  
problem. What irks residents is Ingraham's attempt to have a 
professional facility in his backyard, and the constant comings and 
goings of players, parents and officials. 
</P>
<P>
	DeSerio and others have suggested that Ingraham charged league  
teams for the use of his field, and brought in professional 
instructors to teach children. Ingraham admits he initially had 
that idea and advertised a ``Field of Dreams Academy'' which 
offered lessons to children and a diamond for a ``35-and-over'' 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said he abandoned the plan after township officials  
objected. 
</P>
<P>
	``People see this and say, `Why would he do this?' So they  
figure money has to be involved,'' Ingraham said. ``They haven't 
found a person who has paid a dime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit seeks to limit the field's use even more than an  
existing court order that permits Ingraham to play only four days a 
week, and only in groups of five or less. Ingraham is seeking 
permission to field full teams for at least 15 hours a week. 
</P>
<P>
	DeSerio, a hairdresser and garden designer who spent years  
restoring her Cape Cod-style home, said she's seen adults and boys 
playing baseball on Sundays, one of the days forbidden in the 
injunction. 
</P>
<P>
	She also said a realtor told her that her property has been  
devalued by up to $30,000 because of the field. And she's bothered 
by a night lighting system that she said floods her upstairs 
bedroom and back yard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to have the integrity of my property returned,'' she  
said. ``It's like living behind a 7-Eleven.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
