<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Sends Regrets to China  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton sent a message of regret  
today to Chinese President Jiang Zemin over the accidental bombing 
of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade, the White House said. National 
security spokesman David Leavy said Clinton expressed ``regret on 
behalf of the American people for the tragic accident, explaining 
that it was not intentional, it was an unfortunate mistake.'' 
Chinese officials said the bombing killed three journalists and 
injured more than 20. But NATO officials today pledged to continue 
airstrikes until Yugoslav President Milosevic accepts a peace plan 
for Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Refugees Celebrate Mom's Day  
</P>
<P>
	FORT DIX, N.J. (AP) -- Refugees from Kosovo celebrated their  
first American holiday today as children presented mothers with 
songs, cards and flowers at a picnic here. But it was hardly a 
happy Mother's Day for all 860 people sheltered at this southern 
New Jersey military post. Many await word of loved ones lost or 
separated during their exodus from the war-torn Yugoslav province. 
Still, soldiers and volunteers tried to keep spirits high with 
music, arts and crafts tables, cake and a clown. ``Urim Nene,'' 
many children wrote on the cards they made, which means ``Greetings 
to Mother.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Plans Nuclear Celebrations  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- The government has planned 18 days of  
celebration to mark the first anniversary of an underground nuclear 
test. The festivities begin tomorrow with public rallies and 
seminars to mark the tests, which took place May 28 and May 30 last 
year. New songs are being written and state-run television is 
planning daily programs to honor the explosions. The government 
says the celebrations are to motivate Pakistan's 140 million people 
to work toward self-reliance. 

</P>
<P>
	Entertainment Heads To Meet Clinton  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton says tomorrow's summit on  
youth violence is about finding answers, not assigning blame. But 
participants from the entertainment industry will be feeling more 
pressure than anyone else there, particularly since the gun lobby 
says it wasn't invited. The Colorado high school massacre has 
stirred debate over whether movies, music and video games have 
helped shape a culture of violence among teens. Meanwhile, the 
National Rifle Association, which met with protests when it held a 
meeting in Denver after the Columbine shootings, said that tomorrow 
it would ``unveil substantial proposals which would have an 
immediate and significant impact on violent crime in America.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Tornado Survivors Worship in Tent  
</P>
<P>
	BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. (AP) -- Hundreds of worshipers gathered in a  
mud-covered tent today for church services, almost a week after a 
deadly tornado ripped through this community. Half of a 
cement-block wall was all that stood at Ridgecrest Baptist Church. 
``I don't know if God took your home, but a tornado did, and God 
will rebuild your life,'' Pastor Tom Duckett told the crowd. Bridge 
Creek, a collection of two churches, a school and 8,000 residents, 
doesn't even appear on a map. It was here that Monday evening's 
tornado started. Eleven Bridge Creek residents died. 

</P>
<P>
	Truck Loaded With Bees Crashes  
</P>
<P>
	FALMOUTH, Maine (AP) -- A truck carrying millions of bees  
overturned on a highway today, leaving its cargo buzzing around the 
wreckage and closing down the roadway for nearly eight hours. The 
truck was carrying between 400 and 450 hives, each home to between 
40,000 and 45,000 bees, a fire official said. He estimated there 
were about 20 million bees on the truck. About five firefighters 
were stung, but none were seriously hurt. On the advice of 
beekeepers, firefighters sprayed the hives with water to calm the 
bees as they loaded them onto another truck. 

</P>
<P>
	Sabres Beat Bruins 3-1  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres evened their playoff series  
with the Boston Bruins and, naturally, they can thank Dominik 
Hasek. The NHL's best goalie weathered a late onslaught for a 3-1 
victory today, rebounding from a 4-2 loss in the second-round 
opener. After gaining a split in Boston, Hasek, the NHL's two-time 
defending MVP, will have the home crowd behind him for Wednesday 
night's third game of the best-of-7 Eastern Conference semifinal. 

</P>
<P>
	Spurs Beat Timberwolves 99-86  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tim Duncan dominated for the Spurs once  
again, scoring 26 points, grabbing 12 rebounds and leading San 
Antonio past the Minnesota Timberwolves 99-86 in Game 1 of their 
playoff series today. The Timberwolves kept the contest close until 
the fourth quarter, when San Antonio opened a comfortable 
double-digit lead. David Robinson had 12 points and eight rebounds 
for the Spurs. Avery Johnson added 21 points and had 10 assists and 
Sean Elliott scored 14 points. Game 2 in the best-of-5 series is 
Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
