<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 14:12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Victims Struggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. (AP) -- For 16 years, Monique and Billy Smith  
led the nomadic life of the military: Arkansas, Louisiana, 
Washington, Iceland, California, Rhode Island. A year and a half 
ago, they moved their three kids into a neat little brick ranch 
house southwest of Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	Perched on a hill overlooking a cow pasture, the house had  
everything. The hardwood floors were good for the kids' asthma. And 
there was finally enough room for each member of the family to set 
aside a quiet space to talk to God -- a prayer closet. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a house we thanked God for every day,'' Mrs. Smith  
said. ``Because it was what we always wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't just a house. It was home.  
</P>
<P>
	The house is a shell now, torn apart by a gang of tornadoes that  
raked the Midwest this week and killed 46 people -- including seven 
of the Smiths' neighbors. The family of five has moved into a 
cramped hotel room miles away in Norman. 
</P>
<P>
	Like thousands of others across the region, the Smiths are  
facing an unknown period in borrowed space before they can rebuild. 
But while they've lost their houses, they're discovering that they 
are not homeless. 
</P>
<P>
	The only thing the Smith children needed to feel at home in the  
hotel was their Bibles. 
</P>
<P>
	For Becky and Chris Pillifant, home will be a relative's  
recreational vehicle until they can rebuild the three-bedroom brick 
house they bought three years ago in Oklahoma City's Southwest 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Pillifant sees living in the recreational vehicle as an  
adventure. ``It's got a great big queen-size bed,'' he says. ``You 
could park it anywhere and live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Pillifant isn't as thrilled with the prospect.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm kind of nervous about it,'' she said, holding a blueberry  
muffin in her bandaged left hand. ``You know how tornadoes love 
trailer homes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It might help if Mrs. Pillifant could decorate the RV with her  
collection of miniature villages, but they're all gone. Instead, 
she'll plaster the camper with pictures of her grandchildren who 
were rescued. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest thing is we're both together,'' her husband said.  
``It makes a home when we're both together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six months ago, Mary and James Huff of Moore took in their grown  
daughter when their son-in-law lost his job. Now, their daughter is 
returning the favor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took them to Wal-Mart and bought them some clothes,'' said  
Sheri Harris, who is putting her two boys in bunk beds to make room 
for her parents in her three-bedroom apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the things that made Mrs. Huff's two-story house a home  
was her collection of family china -- three generations of it 
lovingly displayed in two cabinets. Not a piece survived. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was me,'' she said sadly. ``It's not replaceable.''  
</P>
<P>
	But neither is she.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care about the china cabinet I was going to get,''  
Mrs. Harris said. ``I've got her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To Mike Wood of Bridge Creek, home meant feeding Sugar, the  
family's 3-year-old buckskin horse, and tending the rows of beets, 
okra and cantaloupe in the garden out back. He took pride in the 
improvements he'd made to the 4-acre plot -- the white fences, the 
barn, the corral. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was it for the rest of our lives,'' he said. ``It wasn't  
no mansion, but it was our home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, for the first time in years, he is living with his mother  
in Oklahoma City, this time with a wife and two children. Daughter 
Angela, 16, is just trying to get used to sharing a sofa-bed with 
her 13-year-old brother, Dane. 
</P>
<P>
	``He kicks real hard,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Sugar is boarding miles away, and there's no room for a garden.  
Wood is wondering how he will breathe until he can rebuild and get 
back to the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you live in town, the houses are so close together you  
can basically jump from roof to roof,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The thing that made Dr. James Rains feel at home in his  
one-story flagstone house was that it made him feel safe. 
</P>
<P>
	``People would ask, `Did you hear the storm?' one night or  
another,'' the Oklahoma City chiropractor said. ``I never heard it, 
this house was built so well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rains and his wife, Toni, are living in a hotel now, but he is  
thinking of planting a trailer where his house once stood. He wants 
to watch the workers put the salvaged building stones back in 
place. He thinks he can recreate that feeling of safety from the 
rubble he crawled out of. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to get the blueprint to do it all over again,'' he  
said as workers used a chain saw to cut up what was once his roof. 
``A lot of people are looking at this as if it's the end. I'm 
looking at it as a new beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some fear they will never feel quite at home again.  
</P>
<P>
	In the midst of the destruction in the city of Moore, Jim and  
Linda Fernandes' home looks relatively untouched. Aside from some 
blown-out windows and a few punctures, the brick-and-wood ranch 
seems intact next to the twisted remains of every other house on 
the street. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fernandes is looking for almost any reason to have to move --  
a split ridge beam in the attic, cracked brickwork under the eaves, 
anything. It seems habitable, but the thought of staying in a 
bulldozed wasteland for long months as others rebuild is just too 
much. If insurance adjustors say it's a complete loss, that OK with 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope they total me,'' the retired federal employee said as  
he crunched through glass shards in his driveway. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fernandeses moved into their home 33 years ago Thursday, the  
first in the neighborhood. They raised two daughters there, had 
their wedding receptions there. He planted flowering Bradford pear 
trees in the back yard and watched the neighbors' kids grow as his 
did. 
</P>
<P>
	At 63, Fernandes doesn't know if he has 33 years to pack such  
memories into another house. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my home, my kids' home, my grandkids' home,'' he said.  
``That's how they'll remember me. That's why I stayed here. It was 
supposed to be a legacy. I was never a mover. ... I'll never feel 
at home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His wife's eyes fill with tears as she tries to reassure him.  
</P>
<P>
	``As long as we have each other, we'll have a home,'' she says.  
``The Lord will put us where he wants us to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Around the corner, Earl Capps is already building a new home in  
his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	When the storms approached Monday evening, the Moore school  
administrator was where he pretty much always was that time of day 
-- sitting in front of the television in his favorite recliner. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's right there; that's my chair,'' he said, pointing across  
the lawn to a broken beige blob with stuffing poking out all over. 
``I've had it about 15 years. It fit me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capps and his wife, Marquita, have traded their three-bedroom  
house for a one-bedroom apartment. They plan to rebuild on the same 
spot -- and he's already keeping an eye out for that next favorite 
chair. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an attitude thing,'' he says. ``Wherever we end up,  
that's going to become home -- whether it's the back of a pickup or 
in a penthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the spirit of Oklahoma. We went through the Murrah  
bombing. We're all survivors,'' he said. ``And once we rebuild and 
we're all back here, we're going to have a block party and 
celebrate life. Celebrate each other.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
