<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 12:11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Singapore Layoffs Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- About 2,800 workers reportedly lost their jobs  
in Singapore in the first three months this year -- a steep drop 
from the 8,000 layoffs in the last quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing figures from the Manpower Ministry, The Sunday Times said  
the unemployment rate in the city-state has dropped to 3.9 percent 
from 4.4 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``But compared to our normal unemployment rate of 2 percent,  
it's still very high,'' Manpower Minister Lee Boon Yang was quoted 
as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	A record 28,300 people were laid off in Singapore last year, the  
highest number since 19,529 jobs were lost in 1985 during the last 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the way to recovery was the manufacturing sector, which  
accounted for 28 percent of layoffs this year. In comparison, 
two-thirds of all layoffs were in the manufacturing industry last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee attributed the industry's recovery to reliance on exports to  
the United States and Europe, where demand was still strong. 
</P>
<P>
	Other sectors, such as finance, commerce and business services,  
were more closely linked to the region, which is still battling the 
economic crisis, Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as our neighboring countries have not made a complete  
recovery, these sectors' prospects will be affected,'' Lee said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
