<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China Protesters Decry NATO Attack  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Furious Chinese demonstrators hurled rocks and  
debris into the U.S. Embassy on Sunday, trapping American diplomats 
inside their compound in a second day of protests against NATO's 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia. Most protesters went 
home early Monday, allowing some diplomats to leave the 
ambassador's residence. There were no demonstrators, but helmeted 
police stood in rows three deep in front of the embassy gate, and 
new police were being moved into the area as if expecting a third 
day of demonstrations. On Sunday, thousands flowed past the main 
U.S. Embassy buildings in Beijing, while others attacked the 
British and Albanian missions and protested at U.S. consulates 
elsewhere. 

</P>
<P>
	CIA Error Blamed for Bombing Mixup  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A CIA error that was based on faulty  
information and then went undetected led to the mistaken NATO 
targeting and bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, a U.S. 
official said today. The official said the intended target, the 
Yugoslav Federal Directorate of Supply and Procurement, was chosen 
by the CIA. Other organizations, including NATO, the U.S. European 
Command and the Pentagon's Joint Staff, approved it. The embassy is 
several hundred yards away from the Yugoslav government office. 
NATO and President Clinton offered further apologies today for the 
bombing. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinians, Israelis Seek Deal  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian and Israeli officials held  
last-minute meetings today over the closing of offices at the PLO's 
headquarters, seeking to avert a confrontation days before Israeli 
elections. Israeli police officials met with a lawyer for the 
Orient House headquarters past a 7 p.m. deadline set by Israel to 
shut down the complex, and negotiators agreed to meet again 
tomorrow. Israel's Cabinet decided earlier this month to close 
three offices in Orient House, saying they had ties to the 
Palestinian Authority that, under interim peace agreements, is not 
allowed to operate in Jerusalem. The Palestinians have said the 
offices are not connected to the authority. 

</P>
<P>
	23 Die in Bus Crash in Louisiana  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- A chartered bus carrying members of a seniors  
casino club on a Mother's Day gambling excursion ran off a highway 
this morning and crashed, killing 23 people, authorities said. 
Seventeen more were hospitalized, nine in critical or guarded 
condition, and three were released after emergency room treatment. 
The bus swerved from the left lane off of the highway, then across 
a narrow paved narrow path for golf carts that emerges from a 
tunnel next to the highway, crashing down one embankment and up the 
other. 

</P>
<P>
	Jenny Jones Defends Show  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Despite a $25 million verdict against her talk  
show, Jenny Jones said in an interview that the program is not to 
blame for the shooting death of a guest who revealed a gay crush on 
another guest. ``I think it's not fair to blame the show for the 
actions of someone. That happened three days after they left the 
show,'' Ms. Jones told ``Dateline NBC'' in an interview broadcast 
today. A jury last week held the show and its corporate owner, 
Warner Bros., liable in the shooting death of Scott Amedure, who 
had revealed his attraction to Jonathan Schmitz during a 1995 
taping of the program. Amedure was shot dead three days later. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices rose in early trading Monday  
amid hopes for fresh measures by the Japanese government to 
stimulate the economy. The Nikkei Stock Average rose 113.89 points 
to 17,060.41 points in the first 30 minutes of trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Lakers Take Opener From Rockets  
</P>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Two clutch defensive plays, a block by  
Shaquille O'Neal and a pounce by Derek Fisher, made the Los Angeles 
Lakers winners today. O'Neal blocked Cuttino Mobley's layup attempt 
from behind at the final buzzer, and Fisher had 20 points, six 
assists, three steals and one crucial recovery of a loose ball as 
the Lakers beat the Houston Rockets 101-100 to open the playoffs. 

</P>
<P>
	Sabres Even Series With Bruins  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres evened their playoff series  
with the Boston Bruins and, naturally, they can thank Dominik 
Hasek. The NHL's best goalie weathered a late onslaught for a 3-1 
victory today, rebounding from a 4-2 loss in the second-round 
opener. The Sabres hope Miroslav Satan, who led them with 40 
regular-season goals, will have recovered enough from a bruised 
foot to return after missing his third straight game. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
</TEXT>
