<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sears To Stay As WNBA Sponsor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. has extended its  
partnership the WNBA for another three years, the first of the 
women's professional basketball league sponsors to renew its 
initial deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms were not disclosed but the deal for the years 2000 through  
2002 includes commercials on Women's National Basketball 
Association telecasts, on-court signs at all WNBA arenas and sales 
of WNBA merchandise in Sears stores. The department store chain's 
current three-year deal extends through this season. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, it was announced that Sears will be the presenting  
sponsor of the first WNBA All-Star game to be held July 14 in New 
York. It will conduct balloting for the teams at its stores as well 
as over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears is among a dozen companies who have been with the WNBA  
since the league's opening season in 1997. Other sponsors include 
General Motors Corp., American Express Co. and Anheuser-Busch Cos. 
</P>
<P>
	The league expands to a dozen teams this season from 10 last  
year. Each team plays a 32-game regular season starting June 10 
with the playoffs winding up near Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	John Lebbad, Sears director of event marketing and sales  
promotion, said Friday that Sears sales have risen as a result of 
its first two years as a WNBA sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the arrangement helps the retailer based in Hoffman  
Estates, Ill., near Chicago strengthen its appeal to its core 
customer -- women between 25 and 54 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Val Ackerman, president of the WNBA, said the league is starting  
to talk with other sponsors about renewing partnership deals. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
