<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bird-Watchers Flock to Lake Erie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAK HARBOR, Ohio (AP) -- Perched atop a leafless branch, a  
red-tailed hawk cries out. Its voice sends a shrill warning across 
the marsh. 
</P>
<P>
	In the air, another hawk circles just above a nest with  
uneasiness, signaling that we are too close. Not wanting to disturb 
them, we move on, the hawk's piercing cry still ringing in our 
ears. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the sound they use in the movies,'' says Christy Smith,  
a biologist with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The hawks are among the 300 species of birds that can be spotted  
along Ohio's Lake Erie coast. Most of the birds pass through during 
the spring migration, stopping at the marshes and rocky shoreline 
to rest and refuel before flying north across the lake for the 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The migration attracts thousands of bird-watchers toting  
expensive binoculars, spotting scopes and high-sensitivity tape 
recorders. They come from all states and around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird-watching is among the most popular activities in the  
nation, according to government surveys. About 60 million people 
say they are bird-watchers, ranging from the backyard variety to 
experts who keep detailed lists of every warbler and shorebird 
they've seen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing about birding is that it's accessible to everyone,''  
says Peter Dunne, director of New Jersey Audubon Society's Cape May 
Bird Observatory. ``No matter where you are, there is a bird within 
100 feet of you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It can be a treasure hunt and a way to escape from everyday  
concerns, he adds. 
</P>
<P>
	States are beginning to cash in on bird tourism, catering to the  
millions of birders who spend about $10 billion a year on hotels, 
campgrounds and restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal regions that are stops on the spring and autumn  
migration trails are wildly popular. The Texas coast along the Gulf 
of Mexico and the Cape May peninsula in southern New Jersey each 
draw more than 100,000 birders a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida's Everglades and southeast Arizona's Sulphur Springs  
Valley also are among the country's top birding sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Migrating birds long have been coming to northern Ohio because  
much of it was swampland more than 200 years ago. Although little 
of that remains, there are still more than 20 good bird-watching 
sites in the area between Toledo and Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of them alone, Ottawa National Wildlife Refuge and the Magee  
Marsh Wildlife Area, have 20,000 acres of marshes, mud flats, 
ponds, grasslands and forests where birds can feast on fish, worms, 
mussels and plants. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're basically a bed-and-breakfast'' for the birds, Smith  
said. ``We try to provide everything they need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While both parks have walking paths and provide information for  
visitors, the Ottawa Wildlife Refuge's focus is on maintaining a 
safe and nurturing habitat for the birds. Access is limited to 
protect herons, egrets and shorebirds, which don't do well with 
humans around. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there are 10 miles of trails through the marshes and  
woodlands. The refuge also has five eagles' nests. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to get a good slice of what's going on,'' Smith  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some birds fly in from as far away as South America. They cross  
the Gulf of Mexico and then follow rivers northward until finding a 
place to mate and spend the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rivers are like highways for them,'' says Mark  
Shieldcastle, a wildlife biologist at Crane Creek. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the lake, the natural areas are as diverse and interesting  
as the birds for some. The walking trails through the marshes and 
woods are flat and meander past ponds. Deer, muskrats and rabbits 
often can be spotted along with eagles, and wildflowers add a 
splash of color in the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly love just being out walking in the woods and marsh  
areas,'' says Mike Crofts, a bird-watcher for more than 25 years. 
``Learning about birds makes it more interesting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During migration, members of the Black Swamp Bird Observatory  
capture birds in nets and fit them with leg bands. Bruce Simpson of 
Delaware, Ohio, makes a four-hour round trip each week to help with 
the banding, which allows biologists to monitor habitat uses and 
migration patterns. They'll net and band up to 250 birds each day 
at the height of the migration. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the number of bird-watchers pales in comparison with  
their feathered friends, as many as 50,000 are expected to crowd 
the Lake Erie shore during May, adding up to $10 million to the 
area economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Many hotels offer discounts for bird-watchers, up to 20 percent  
off room rates, and gladly fill a thermos with coffee for early 
morning outings. 
</P>
<P>
	At least two of the passenger boat lines that serve the lake  
have added special birding excursions in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jet Express, which operates out of Port Clinton, shuttles  
birders to Point Pelee National Park in Canada and has birding 
experts on board during the 35-mile trip. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Some tips if you go bird-watching in northern Ohio:  
</P>
<P>
	GETTING THERE: The Ottawa Wildlife National Refuge and the Magee  
Marsh Wildlife Area are side-by-side along the Lake Erie shore. 
Toledo is 25 miles to the west, Cleveland 80 miles to the east. 
Interstate 75 and the Ohio Turnpike are within 20 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	BIRDING EVENTS: The Midwest Birding Symposium will be in  
Lakeside Sept. 16-19. The program will feature seminars with 
birding experts, field trips and a sale of bird-watchers' supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	THE WEATHER: Be sure to bring a raincoat and an extra sweater.  
April and May can be unpredictable. 
</P>
<P>
	GEAR: Bring binoculars. An expensive pair isn't necessary to  
notice each bird's unique colors and markings. 
</P>
<P>
	CLOTHING: Wear comfortable clothes and shoes. Include a rain  
jacket and hat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
