<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> President Sends Regrets to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton sent a message of regret  
Sunday to Chinese President Jiang Zemin, explaining the bombing of 
the Chinese embassy in Belgrade as ``an unfortunate mistake,'' the 
White House said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also spoke by telephone Sunday with French President  
Jacques Chirac to discuss the NATO mission in Yugoslavia and 
diplomatic efforts with Russia, said national security spokesman 
David Leavy. 
</P>
<P>
	Leavy said Clinton sent a message to Jiang ``expressing regret  
on behalf of the American people for the tragic accident, 
explaining that it was not intentional, it was an unfortunate 
mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Clinton's letter ``also made clear the importance of  
guaranteeing the safety of our personnel and the protection of the 
(U.S.) embassy staff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 20-minute call to Chirac, both leaders agreed ``that  
accidents like this are inevitable,'' Leavy said. ``Both leaders 
agree that the air campaign has to continue, that the alliance will 
remain united and continue to prosecute the air campaign until 
NATO's conditions are met.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Chirac also discussed the diplomatic dialogue with  
Russia, and agreed it is necessary to continue to engaging Russia 
and other European nations on ``the requirements to end NATO's 
bombing and give the Kosovars the security and dignity they 
deserve,'' Leavy said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
