<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Up in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices rose in early trading Monday  
amid hopes for fresh measures by the Japanese government to 
stimulate the economy. The U.S. dollar was higher against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 113.89 points,  
or 0.67 percent, to 17,060.41 points in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. On Friday, the average lost 354.09 points, or 2.05 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was traded at 120.94 yen, up 0.40 yen from late in  
Tokyo on Friday and also above its late New York level of 120.85 
yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock exchange, share prices jumped following comments  
Sunday by Japan's chief economic planner, Taichi Sakaiya, that an 
extra budget to spur economic growth was ``possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were also boosted by strong gains Friday on Wall Street.  
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 84.77 points 
to 11,031.59, marking yet another record close. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 7.28 points, or 0.53 percent, to 1,375.70. The 
TOPIX closed down 12.70 points, or 0.92 percent Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar rose on U.S. employment data  
released last week that showed job growth remained strong in 
America despite a slight rise in unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 129.55 yen, down  
from 130.22 yen late Friday in Tokyo. The euro fell on news of the 
North Atlantic Treaty Organization's mistaken bombing of the 
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.335 percent from 1.315 percent Friday, driving it's 
price down to 104.13 yen from 104.32 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
