<HEADLINE> Noted MD Denies Sex Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A noted epidemiologist who left his posts at  
Harvard Medical School and Brigham and Women's Hospital in March 
resigned amid allegations of sexual harassment, according to a 
published report. 
</P>
<P>
	The physician denied the claims.  
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Globe on Sunday reported allegations that Dr. Charles  
H. Hennekens harassed more than a dozen women over several years, 
basing its report on three unidentified sources who worked with 
Hennekens at the hospital's Division of Preventive Medicine,. 
</P>
<P>
	Hennekens, 56, criticized the Globe for relying on anonymous  
sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``In today's world, allegations of sexual harassment are easily  
made and difficult to disprove. When they are made by people who 
are unwilling to be identified, they are not worthy of response, 
much less publication,'' Hennekens said in a statement issued by 
his lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since the Globe has chosen to publish anonymous allegations, I  
will state only that I have never in my life sexually harassed 
anyone in the division or anywhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hennekens led the landmark study that found taking an aspirin a  
day cuts the risk of some kinds of heart attacks. He also is noted 
for leading studies that found birth control pills don't raise the 
risk of heart attacks and that low-fat diets don't prevent breast 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	When he resigned in March, he cited ``personal and family  
illness'' and his lawyer, Joel Kozol, said Hennekens wanted to move 
to Florida to be with his ailing mother. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Brigham and Women's spokeswoman Christine Baratta and  
Harvard spokesman Bill Shaller declined to comment on the reason 
for Hennekens' departure, citing ``issues of employee 
confidentiality.'' Hennekens' lawyer did not immediately return 
phone messages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
