<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Town Too Nice for Telemarketers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FROSTBURG, Md. (AP) -- Judy Blackburn has nothing but good things  
to say about her job at Unitel Corp. ``I LOVE working here. I LOVE 
this place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But only as long as her employer doesn't send her back to making  
cold calls as a telemarketer, with pitches for long-distance 
telephone service or overnight package deliveries. 
</P>
<P>
	Since January, she's been taking calls instead, from folks with  
questions about retirement accounts. She's in Customer Service, and 
for Blackburn, in a much better job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had people tell me I ruined their day by calling them, that  
I should be ashamed of myself,'' she says of her earlier task. 
</P>
<P>
	Not very nice. Not the kind of person you'll likely meet in  
Frostburg, if you believe Blackburn's employer. 
</P>
<P>
	Unitel says modest, accommodating people outnumber brash,  
assertive people by such a wide margin in this Appalachian town of 
8,100 that it can only fill 100 sales jobs here. 
</P>
<P>
	So the telemarketing firm based in Virginia is turning the bulk  
of its 400 positions in Frostburg toward customer service and 
concentrating its sales work in a calling center opening later in 
May in Lakeland, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	There, by tapping a population of more than 200,000 between  
Tampa and Orlando, Unitel President Douglas Palley is sure he'll 
find more people able to do the grunt work of telemarketing. 
</P>
<P>
	The meat-eaters, he calls them. The Type A's.  
</P>
<P>
	``Type A is where, if you're at a party, they'll walk up to you  
and say `My name is whatever.' Type B is the type that sits there 
and waits for someone to come over,'' Palley says. ``I think, in 
the general population, the minority of people are Type A 
personalities, and those are the types of people you need to make 
100 phone calls a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Carmichael, a vice president at Unitel, says most of the  
company's Frostburg team isn't the ``assertive, aggressive sort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Mayor John Bambacus insists, in words for which he later  
apologized, ``Frostburg is not the Bronx.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not by a long shot. It's part old coal-mining town and part  
modern college town, near the Eastern Continental Divide. It's 10 
miles from West Virginia and 150 miles from Baltimore, tucked among 
the peaks of Maryland's mountainous western panhandle. 
</P>
<P>
	Allegany County's unemployment is high -- 9.7 percent in  
February, more than double the state and national rates. But so is 
worker absenteeism during deer-hunting season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a laid-back community. We take things a little  
slower,'' says the mayor, also a professor of political science at 
Frostburg State University, as he drives his Dodge pickup along 
Main Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Princess Restaurant hasn't changed much in 60 years: A  
plaque above one yellow Formica table marks the booth where Harry 
and Bess Truman ate in 1953. Movie tickets at the Palace Theater 
are $5, all the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Parking tickets -- rarely issued -- carry a $1 fine. The most  
alarming crimes that the 14-member police force investigated last 
year included the theft of the town Christmas tree from a lot 
between City Hall and the First Presbyterian Church. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph Race, a former bank president and current raconteur, likes  
it this way. The area's character, he says, was shaped by pious 
German farmers and immigrants from Italy and the British Isles who 
came to mine coal in the hills covered with hardwoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors pull together during crises, like the tornado that  
leveled 29 homes last year, but otherwise they tend to be reserved 
and clannish. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Italians didn't get along with the Irish,'' Race notes.  
``The Scots all went to the Presbyterian church and had little or 
no use for the Roman Catholic church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he loves his town enough to have spent most of his 91  
years here, he cautions against concluding its citizens are 
exceptionally nice, just because they don't like making sales 
pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe they're too lazy,'' he snorts. ``Have you thought of  
that?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bambacus says Frostburg takes pride in its neighborliness. But  
so does the Bronx, adds borough spokesman Clint Roswell. ``The pace 
might be a little faster living in a city,'' he says, ``but I can't 
see it having an effect on people being assertive or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And what's wrong with assertiveness, asks Lakeland Mayor Buddy  
Fletcher, a developer of strip malls and office buildings. 
``Assertive is always good in whatever we do in the sales field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Would he like to be a telemarketer?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm more of a people person,'' Fletcher says.  
</P>
<P>
	So is Charlotte Biggs of Frostburg. This 35-year-old divorced  
mother likes her customer service job at Unitel, but she hates 
making sales pitches. ``I don't like them calling me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Who does? Even Betty Williams, a retired receptionist who has  
lived in the Frostburg area for all her 71 years, cuts off 
telemarketers. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they start talking, I say, `I'm not interested, thank  
you,' and hang up,'' she admits, during a lunchtime chat at the 
Princess Restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	Her pal Betty Kahl, retired postmistress, treats telemarketers  
more gently. When they call, she listens. After all, it might be 
her neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
	The one who works at Unitel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
