<HEADLINE> Oscar-Winner Dench Up for Tony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Judi Dench may be headed for a rare double.  
</P>
<P>
	The recent Academy Award winner for ``Shakespeare in Love'' is  
up for a Tony thanks to her work on Broadway in the play ``Amy's 
View.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very dreamlike,'' Dench, 64, says in Sunday's Daily News.  
``I'm like the cartoon character that runs off the cliff,'' and 
hangs suspended in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	A top actress in England for decades, Dench gained attention in  
America playing Queen Victoria in ``Mrs. Brown'' before her 
Oscar-winning turn in ``Shakespeare in Love'' as Queen Elizabeth. 
Her other film credits include two James Bond films ``GoldenEye'' 
and ``Tomorrow Never Dies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She co-stars in ``Tea With Mussolini,'' a film by Franco  
Zeffirelli opening Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Amy's View,'' she plays an actress coming to grips with old  
age. 
</P>
<P>
	``Throughout your life, you get wiser. You get more  
economical,'' Dench said. ``It isn't the most you do, it's the less 
you do that's most important.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
