<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Timetable Set in Rebuilding Bulls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Bulls chairman Jerry Reinsdorf, whose  
team is headed for the draft lottery instead of defending its 
championship, isn't sure how long it will take to produce a winner 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The shorter the better. But you can't set a timetable. We just  
have to make progress every year,'' Reinsdorf said Sunday before 
the other team he runs, the Chicago White Sox, played the Oakland 
Athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulls just completed a miserable season, going 13-37 after  
breaking up their dynasty. It was a season full of lopsided losses 
and embarrassing records for futility, such as scoring 49 points in 
one game and losing by 47 points in another. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a done deal now and the challenge is to rebuild it and  
get it back to where it was,'' Reinsdorf said. The draft lottery is 
May 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Jordan recently broke off negotiations to buy the  
Charlotte Hornets because he wanted more control than owner George 
Shinn was willing to give. Reinsdorf seemed to think the deal could 
be revived. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you can assume that the deal is done unless  
Shinn makes a deal with somebody else. ... It can come back to life 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White Sox chopped their payroll to $24 million this season  
after letting Albert Belle and Robin Ventura go. They are stressing 
a youth movement after drawing just 1.39 million fans last year and 
have gotten off to a good start, two games over .500 before 
Sunday's play. Still, crowds have been small and in 12 home dates 
before Sunday, the White Sox were averaging 12,541. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our TV ratings have definitely gone up. Ticket sales are  
picking up,'' Reinsdorf said. ``If we play well and once the 
weather gets nice, people will come out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't pay attention to it. I just come out. I'm not worried  
about it. If we continue to play well into the future, we will be 
OK.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
