<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 23:52:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars, Blues Set for Game 3 / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The playoff experience Joe Nieuwendyk missed  
last year is putting him into overdrive this postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Stars center is among the league leaders in scoring  
heading into Game 3 of the second-round series tonight against the 
St. Louis Blues. He was at his best in Game 2 Saturday night with 
two goals, including the game-winner in overtime, and an assist 
that put the Stars ahead 2-0 in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it chewed him up inside that he wasn't a part of the  
playoff run last year,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``He's making 
the most of it this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nieuwendyk, who sat out all but one game of the playoffs last  
year with a knee injury, has five goals and two assists. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was awful difficult watching last year,'' Nieuwendyk said.  
``That's a big part of it. I'm feeling good and I'm excited, I'm 
playing on adrenaline and having a lot of fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Too much fun for the Blues. Nieuwendyk had several other great  
scoring chances in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's obviously a world-class player,'' Blues winger Blair  
Atcheynum said. ``He's been a sparkplug in this series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game also is Brett Hull's first postseason appearance in St.  
Louis since he left as a free agent last summer. Hull has been 
downplaying the situation, citing frequent player turnover during 
his Blues' career. 
</P>
<P>
	``For 10 years in St. Louis, it was like I played on 10  
different teams,'' Hull said. ``There was never anybody there for 
more than a year or two except Grant Fuhr and Al MacInnis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars' fast start has the Blues back in familiar territory,  
trying to climb out of a hole. St. Louis rallied from a 3-1 series 
deficit to beat the Phoenix Coyotes in the first round, and the job 
this round already may be tougher considering the Stars were No. 1 
overall in the NHL in the regular season and are 6-0 in the 
playoffs thus far. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Game 2 could have gone either way. So nobody  
is uttering the dreaded ``backs-against-the-wall'' bromide yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dallas is on a great winning streak and I'm sure they feel  
they're in control,'' Blues coach Joel Quenneville said. ``I love 
the way we battled. It's a frustrating loss, but we proved to 
ourselves like we did in Game 3 against Phoenix that if you play 
like that, you find a way to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues didn't win Game 3 against Phoenix, but didn't quit  
after a poor start from goalie Grant Fuhr put them behind 4-0 early 
in the second period. The final was 5-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock certainly wasn't crowing after Game 2, which was  
filled with odd-man rushes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope I never see another game like that again,''  
Hitchcock said. ``That was one revved-up hockey game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues got a strong game Saturday from Pierre Turgeon, who  
had a goal and two assists after getting slashed on the back of the 
left knee by Pat Verbeek in Game 1. Turgeon had been a doubtful 
starter. 
</P>
<P>
	Verbeek and the Blues' Jamal Mayers, who took a retaliatory  
slash at Darryl Sydor in that game, will return tonight after 
serving one-game suspensions. 
</P>
<P>
	Quenneville also prodded Pavol Demitra, the team's leading  
scorer in the regular season, into productivity by putting him on 
the fourth line with enforcers Tony Twist and Tyson Nash. Demitra, 
who had been a team-worst minus-4 in the playoffs, had two goals. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis didn't practice Sunday after arriving home at about 3  
a.m., concluding a stretch where they were on the road 26 of 34 
days. Their flight was delayed when smoke filled the plane's cabin 
before departure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
