<DOCNO> APW19990509.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 16:12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mutombo Wins IBM Stats Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dikembe Mutombo of the Atlanta Hawks is the  
winner of the NBA's IBM award, a computer-generated measure of a 
player's statistical contributions to his team. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutombo, who helped lead Atlanta to a 31-19 record by averaging  
10.8 points, 12.2 rebounds and 2.94 blocked shots, finished with a 
115.67 computer rating. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaquille O'Neal of the Lakers was second with a rating of  
102.86, Miami's Alonzo Mourning was third (100.63), followed by 
Detroit's Grant Hill (98.49) and Utah's Karl Malone (98.27). 
</P>
<P>
	Malone won the award last season, and David Robinson has won it  
five times. Michael Jordan won it twice. 
</P>
<P>
	The rating is derived from a complicated formula: Points, field  
goal attempts, rebounds, assists, steals and blocks are added 
together, and personal fouls and turnovers are subtracted. That sum 
is added to the number of a team's victories multiplied by 10, and 
that total is multiplied by 250 to reach a number that is divided 
by team points minus field goal attempts plus rebounds, assists, 
steals and blocks minus personal fouls and turnovers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutombo's award was announced Sunday. The Sixth Man Award will  
be announced Monday and the All-Defensive team will be named 
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
