<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nome Wants To Honor Ties to Earp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NOME, Alaska (AP) -- This still untamed Gold Rush town wants  
Kevin Costner to help celebrate its 100th birthday this summer, 
along with anybody else who played Wyatt Earp in the movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Earp's enduring fame comes from being a marshal in Tombstone,  
Ariz., site of the legendary 1882 shootout at the OK Corral. Less 
well-known is that he spent two years in turn-of-the-century Nome 
at a time when the city's beaches were surrendering tons of gold to 
frenzied prospectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Farflung even by Alaska standards, the city of 4,000 remains a  
saucy, frontier town, perhaps best known as the finish of the 
Iditarod Sled Dog Race. Fittingly, the courting of Costner, an 
Oscar-winner for ``Dances With Wolves,'' isn't being pursued with 
much reverence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a wolf I want danced with,'' wisecracked Cussy Kauer,  
one of the Earp party organizers. ``I've got him chained up in 
front of my house in case he shows up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the Fourth of July centennial celebration, Nome has sent  
Costner a formal invitation for what's being billed as ``Wyatt Earp 
Weekend,'' complete with a gunfight on the town's main street. 
</P>
<P>
	The star of the 1994 film ``Wyatt Earp'' hasn't accepted, but he  
hasn't declined, unlike Kurt Russell, who played Earp in 1993's 
``Tombstone.'' He'll be shooting a movie overseas in July. 
</P>
<P>
	The late Henry Fonda, James Stewart and Burt Lancaster all  
portrayed Earp on celluloid, along with Randolph Scott and Joel 
McCrea. So did James Garner. Even Ronald Reagan took a turn, in 
``Law and Order'' in 1953. 
</P>
<P>
	Of all the Earp movies, Costner's gets closest to Alaska -- its  
final scene shows him on a ship approaching the Bering Sea coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Why Wyatt?  
</P>
<P>
	``I want to draw as much attention as possible to Nome,'' said  
Laura Samuelson, a local museum director and the party's organizer. 
``I want to expose Nome's history from the beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And at the beginning, Earp was there.  
</P>
<P>
	Nome in those early days was the Wild North, a place that could  
certainly have used the talents of a seasoned lawman. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a den of iniquity, probably unequaled anywhere,'' said  
Howard Clifford, who is writing a book about Earp's life in Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	But like everyone else, Earp came to Alaska to make money. He  
built a saloon -- the first wooden building in this treeless corner 
of the globe -- that made him rich. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of the better times of his life,'' said Clifford of  
Seattle. ``He wrote a letter to his brothers saying he was making a 
fortune mining the miners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to hook a celebrity is tough when the destination is far  
away and the budget is tight, organizers said. Even efforts to land 
a TV star, Hugh O'Brien, who got famous portraying Earp in the 
early years of television, have fallen flat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
