<HEADLINE> Cosby Tells Graduates: Move Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORANGEBURG, S.C. (AP) -- Speaking to new graduates of Claflin  
College, Bill Cosby made a plea for beleaguered parents everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the name of God move on,'' Cosby said Saturday. ``Because a  
house can't take three grown people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The actor and comedian sported a Claflin T-shirt and cap,  
sweatpants and tennis shoes. His wry observations about parenthood 
drew raucous laughter and applause from both parents and students. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of you are going back home and people are not happy,'' he  
told graduates of the historically black college. 
</P>
<P>
	Cosby recalled his college days at Temple University in  
Philadelphia, where his favorite subjects were political science 
and philosophy because professors asked questions that no one could 
answer. 
</P>
<P>
	One professor wanted to know if a glass was half full or half  
empty. Cosby returned to class with the wisdom of his grandmother, 
who told him that ``it depends on if you're drinking or pouring.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
