<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 16:41:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Bring Spencer Back Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Yankees reshuffled their left  
fielders yet again today, sending slumping World Series hero Ricky 
Ledee down to the minors and bringing back Shane Spencer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees announced the move shortly after Ledee, playing as a  
pinch-runner, scored the final run in the eighth inning of a 6-1 
victory over Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Ledee, 25, was optioned to Triple-A Columbus and Spencer, 27,  
was recalled from the International League club. 
</P>
<P>
	Ledee, who went 6-for-10 and drove in four runs during the  
Yankees' sweep of San Diego last October, was hitting just .200 
(9-for-45) with no home runs and five RBIs. He had struck out 15 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer, a September sensation with the Yankees, started this  
season with New York before being farmed out on April 29. At the 
time, he had not played in 11 days and was only 2-for-11 with two 
RBIs for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt this was the move to make at this time,'' Yankees  
interim manager Don Zimmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was in a little rut, offensively and defensively,'' he said  
of Ledee. ``The best thing for him is to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chad Curtis started in left field for the Yankees on Sunday,  
scoring three runs and stealing a base. He is hitting just .161, 
but his 14 walks boosted his on-base percentage to .339. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer did well after being sent to Columbus. Going into  
Sunday, he was batting .344 (11-for-32) with one homer and four 
RBIs in eight games for the Clippers. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer and Ledee each created quite a stir for the Yankees late  
last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Ledee saw limited time in the regular season, and did not have a  
hit in the first two rounds of the playoffs. He then became the 
first rookie outfielder to start for the Yankees in the World 
Series since Tom Tresh in 1962, and hit a two-run double off Kevin 
Brown in his first at-bat in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer, who had spent nine years in the minors, enjoyed an  
incredible rookie year. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer hit .373 with 10 home runs and 27 RBIs in only 67  
at-bats, and became only the seventh Yankees player to hit three 
grand slams in a season. He also hit two home runs against Texas in 
the first round of the playoffs 
</P>
<P>
	Based on that, big things were predicted for both Ledee and  
Spencer, particularly after Darryl Strawberry's physical and legal 
problems took him out of the left-field mix early this year. But 
neither of them produced much after making the opening-day roster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
