<DOCNO> APW19990509.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 12:41:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mutombo Rules Middle As Hawks Win  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- In a melancholy mood, Dikembe Mutombo reflected  
Sunday on the death of his mother and the dominant role he played 
in Atlanta's first victory of the NBA playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detroit Pistons preferred to focus on Mutombo's elbows.  
</P>
<P>
	The 7-foot-2 center scored 17 points, grabbed 19 rebounds,  
blocked six shots and dished out a couple of lethal elbows during 
Atlanta's 90-70 thrashing of the Pistons in Game 1 of the best-of-5 
series Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams spent the off day working out at the Georgia Dome,  
where Game 2 will be held Monday night before the series shifts to 
Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're approaching this stage of your career, you want to  
accomplish something big,'' said Mutombo, a two-time Defensive 
Player of the Year who's still seeking his first championship at 
age 32. ``I love being the top defensive player in the game, but I 
want to be on top. I want to get a ring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mutombo played a key role as the Hawks held Detroit to the  
lowest playoff output in team history. The Pistons went more than 
7 1/2 minutes in the third quarter without scoring and finished with 
only 27 points in the second half. 
</P>
<P>
	``He takes away all the easy baskets you normally get,'' said  
Joe Dumars, who was held to three points on 1-of-5 shooting. ``In 
most games, you can count on five or six easy baskets. He 
eliminates that. And when you're not getting those 10 or 12 points, 
it makes it tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On his way to the Georgia Dome, Mutombo made a detour to pick up  
teammate Alan Henderson, who isn't able to drive because of double 
vision caused by an abrasion on his left eye. When Mutombo arrived, 
Henderson was on the phone wishing his mom a happy Mother's Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutombo's own mother died seven months ago after she was denied  
medical help in war-torn Congo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish she was still around,'' he said, a pained expression on  
his face. ``I still love her. I still miss her. It bothers me a lot 
when days like this come around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pistons are perturbed about Mutombo's wicked elbows, which  
were responsible for a few broken noses during the regular season 
and inflicted more damage in the first game of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindsey Hunter arrived at the dome looking like the loser in a  
heavyweight title fight. He could barely open his right eye, which 
was badly bruised after colliding with a Mutombo elbow in the 
opening minute. Later in the game, Christian Laettner took a blow 
to the face. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ridiculous,'' Detroit coach Alvin Gentry said. ``The guy  
already broke three people's noses during a 50-game regular season. 
It's got to stop, one way or the other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mutombo was not called for a foul on either play.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it was done intentionally or not,'' Gentry  
said. ``But the rule book says if you get hit by an elbow, it's got 
to be a foul. Somewhere along the line, it's got to be corrected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter apparently had trouble seeing the basket, hitting only  
2-of-9 from the field and finishing with seven points. But then, no 
Detroit player other than Grant Hill scored in double figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks seem intent of letting Hill get his inevitable points  
-- he had a game-high 26 -- and shutting down the rest of the Pistons 
offense. Hill made 10-of-18 from the field, but the rest of the 
team hit less than 32 percent on 18-of-57 shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Gentry said it was important for the Pistons' big men -- Bison  
Dele, Eric Montross, Jerome Williams and Laettner -- to draw Mutombo 
away from the basket by hitting some outside shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``To go inside against Mutombo is not the most intelligent thing  
in the world,'' Gentry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter is expected to play despite his sore eye, but the  
prognosis isn't as promising for Henderson. He played only four 
minutes in the opener -- wearing a special pair of goggles to help 
cope with the double vision -- and sat on sideline during Sunday's 
practice, a patch covering his injured eye. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very difficult to see,'' said Henderson, unsure when he  
will be fully recovered. ``It's a very slow process, very hard to 
pinpoint.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
