<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hornets Owner Starts Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- George Shinn has started over in a search  
for a partner to share ownership of the NBA Charlotte Hornets. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Jordan said Saturday he broke off negotiations with  
Shinn because of a disagreement over how much control over 
basketball operations the former Chicago Bulls star would have. 
After the announcement Shinn said other interested people have 
approached him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since the discussions between Michael and I were announced, I  
have received numerous inquiries from others who are interested in 
the possibility of a partnership in the Hornets,'' Shinn said in a 
statement released Saturday night. ``Out of respect for Michael and 
the discussions that we were conducting, I did not follow up on any 
of those inquiries. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point I plan to review those opportunities and proceed  
accordingly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn did not mention any names, but at least one has been  
mentioned before. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Johnson, chief executive officer of Black Entertainment  
Television, has said he had no interest in becoming a partner but 
would like to buy the team outright, something Jordan said Friday 
he had offered to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn said he ``tried to be flexible'' in the negotiations with  
Jordan but said he is not willing to give up all control or sell 
the entire franchise to Jordan ``even at a higher price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After exchanging several proposals, the two came to an impasse  
this week over the issue of control. Shinn offered to sell Jordan 
half of the franchise for ``several million dollars'' below 50 
percent of Shinn's market-value price of $160 million and would 
give Jordan control over all basketball operations, including 
salaries, and an equal voice in all business matters, sources told 
The Charlotte Observer. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan also said he was willing to re-open negotiations, but  
only if it was done soon and did not include control as an open 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's up to George,'' Jordan said. ``I could not accept a  
situation where I could not (have final say). 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm open-minded. But it's a dead issue on the control issue.  
We can always accommodate his financial pressures.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
