<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 11:51:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Telekom Eyes Brit Phone Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Deutsche Telekom AG is expected to make a $16  
billion offer for One-2-One, the British mobile phone company owned 
by Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC and MediaOne Group Inc., the Sunday 
Business newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom declined to comment on the report. Officials at  
the other companies could not immediately be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday Business said Deutsche Telekom's offer was expected in  
the next few days, but would have to compete with strong bids from 
companies such as Mannesmann AG, Vivendi of France, France Telecom, 
Bell Atlantic Corp. and Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless has said that no final decision has yet been  
made about One-2-One, according to the paper. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom already is involved in merger talks with  
Telecom Italia SpA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 12:32:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clapton Sees No-Booze New Year Bash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Eric Clapton is planning a New Year's Eve party  
for people who don't want to greet the millennium in an alcoholic 
haze. 
</P>
<P>
	Clapton, who stopped drinking almost 12 years ago and also  
battled drug addiction, told the British Broadcasting Corp. on 
Sunday that he will play with a band during the invitation-only 
party, which will be held at an undisclosed location in the English 
countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	``We devised this little thing where we put on a dance,'' he  
said. ``It's all very secret. It's like a little gathering of 
people who don't drink anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The guitarist best-known for the classic rock song ``Layla''  
said the idea was prompted by past New Year's Eves, which he called 
``the worst night of the year for people who don't drink.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I used to watch New Year's Eve on TV and feel really miserable  
and lonely and think `I'm not drinking.' There's nowhere I can go, 
you know, as a sober person,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Clapton opened a non-profit rehabilitation clinic on  
the Caribbean Island of Antigua. He told the BBC he also has worked 
as an unpaid volunteer at the Priory Clinic in London, a 
rehabilitation facility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0088 </DOCNO>
