<DOCNO> APW19990509.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 15:01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Telekom Eyes Brit Phone Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Deutsche Telekom AG is expected to make a $16  
billion offer for One-2-One, the British mobile phone company owned 
by Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC and MediaOne Group Inc., the Sunday 
Business newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom declined to comment on the report. Officials at  
the other companies could not immediately be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday Business said Deutsche Telekom's offer was expected in  
the next few days, but would have to compete with strong bids from 
companies such as Mannesmann AG, Vivendi of France, France Telecom, 
Bell Atlantic Corp. and Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless has said that no final decision has yet been  
made about One-2-One, according to the paper. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom already is involved in merger talks with  
Telecom Italia SpA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 15:11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers Donate Time To Help Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jean Male is a tax lawyer, but she also makes  
time for a different kind of client -- an abused child who can only 
pay for her services with handmade pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	Male is among about 200 lawyers trained by the nonprofit group  
Lawyers for Children America to provide free legal help to abused 
and neglected children. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it means something to the child that I'm somebody who  
is there for them and is no one else's attorney,'' Male said. 
``This child makes pictures for me and gives them to me. That's 
pretty special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aviation lawyer Louise Cobbs says her volunteer work for a  
pre-teen girl who alleges she was molested by a relative is a 
challenge, but a rewarding one. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can see an immediate impact on the life of the child,''  
Cobbs said. ``It's nice to know that this child is at least safe 
for the time being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before taking on those cases, Male and Cobbs were trained by  
Lawyers for Children America on how to handle them -- a big switch 
from their specialties. 
</P>
<P>
	Begun in 1994 as an in-house legal aid program at Aetna Life &AMP;  
Casualty in Hartford, Conn., the nonprofit group now offers 
training in three other Connecticut cities as well as in Washington 
and Miami, where law firms have donated office space. 
</P>
<P>
	A committed attorney ``could really change the nature of the  
case and whole future for this child,'' Juliet McKenna, one of two 
program directors in the Washington office, told lawyers at a 
recent training session. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, children removed from their homes in abuse or  
neglect cases are appointed a lawyer, either a court appointee or a 
Lawyers for Children volunteer. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys named to represent a child also serve as ``guardian ad  
litem,'' someone whose role is to represent the child's best 
interests even if that is not exactly what the child wants. The 
child does not live with the guardian, but most often is placed 
with a relative or in a foster home. 
</P>
<P>
	Child abuse and neglect proceedings are civil cases, although  
the abuser also may face criminal charges. The goal is to ensure a 
safe, permanent home for the child, either reunited with one or 
both parents or with an adoptive family. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to representing the child in court, the volunteer  
lawyer must meet with the child regularly and make sure his or her 
needs are being met. 
</P>
<P>
	``While you are always the lawyer for the child, you have to  
define your advocacy role as very broad,'' McKenna said. Attorneys 
often find themselves doing things ``you would never do in your day 
job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes it helps to get the child a familiar object from home,  
she said. Or perhaps the child needs new eyeglasses or wants to 
attend religious services. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaining the child's trust is a crucial first step, and it isn't  
always easy, said Dr. Nora Galil, a psychiatrist with Children's 
National Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``The normal, average child is going to kind of look you over  
and not immediately become your best friend,'' Galil said. Start 
with non-threatening topics like school or favorite television 
shows, she said. ``If they're comfortable talking with you about 
small things, they're usually comfortable about talking about 
bigger things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Try not to show surprise at what the child says because it might  
make them clam up, Galil said, adding, ``Some of these kids live 
through some unbelievable things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Visiting the child's home is part of the job, and the lawyers  
were told to be ready for economic and cultural differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to look like your house. It's going to be  
small,'' with many children, said Trudy Mitchell-Gilkey, a social 
worker with the Child and Family Services Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Children staffers go with volunteer lawyers to  
initial court appearances and are available to offer advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We go on the assumption that they don't have expertise in this  
area,'' said Lesley Mara, the organization's executive director in 
Hartford. ``They cannot know all of the possible things that can 
happen to them in a case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Greg Yates, who attended the training session,  
practices commercial real estate and bankruptcy law. He said his 
status as a new father ``got me thinking about how I could make a 
difference. There are so many people who need legal services and it 
doesn't take a whole lot of time to provide it.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 15:23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Left Wondering in Knicks Win  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- One day after the Miami Heat's worst playoff loss  
in two years, a team built on intensity and hustle was stunned to 
see just how feeble an effort they could produce. 
</P>
<P>
	``Terrible, with a capital T,'' center Alonzo Mourning said  
Sunday after two hours of watching film of Miami's 95-75 loss to 
the New York Knicks in the opener of their first-round series. ``We 
just didn't look like a professional basketball team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game 2 of the best-of-5 series is Monday night at Miami Arena,  
where the Knicks now have embarrassed the Heat twice in the past 2 1/2 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to want to make a statement, get their fans  
behind them again,'' Knicks forward Kurt Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday was the Heat's worst playoff defeat since a 98-74 loss  
to Chicago in the 1997 Eastern Conference finals. At least then 
they had the excuse of being whipped by Michael Jordan and Scottie 
Pippen. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no such rejoinders this time. Saturday's loss went  
against just about everything the Heat holds sacred. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wakes you up,'' said Dan Majerle, who scored one point in  
28 minutes. ``If you'd have asked anybody last night if we played 
hard, we'd have said yes. Then you look at the film and realize 
you're not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York shot 53 percent from the floor, going 5-of-10 from  
3-point range. During the regular season, only four Heat opponents 
managed to hit half their shots. 
</P>
<P>
	On offense, Miami got 27 points from Mourning but otherwise  
settled for outside shots. Take away Mourning's 10-for-16 
performance, and the Heat shot just 27 percent (17-for-62). Even 
when the Heat worked free inside, Majerle and Jamal Mashburn missed 
uncontested layups. 
</P>
<P>
	``The eye doesn't lie,'' said forward P.J. Brown, spared from  
the final moments Saturday after he was ejected with 7:48 left. 
``Once you put a camera on it, there's not much you can say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy gave the Heat more credit.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought Miami executed well, but at the end they missed.  
They had wide, wide open 3-point shots. Our defense was not very 
good in that respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heat coach Pat Riley has dealt with similar situations before.  
His Los Angeles Lakers were victims of the 1985 ``Mother's Day 
Massacre,'' a 148-114 loss to Boston in Game 1 of the NBA Finals. 
The Lakers recovered to win the championship in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any team that has lost the first game, you've got to deal with  
the hit,'' Riley said. ``That's the big thing. You've got to deal 
with it and move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of particular concern for the Heat is finding a way to defend  
New York's suddenly diverse offense. 
</P>
<P>
	For more than a decade, the Knicks ran many of their plays  
through Patrick Ewing. Trades for Marcus Camby and Latrell Sprewell 
were made with the idea of opening things up, but they spent a 
frustrating regular season trying to work into the flow. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing's chronic Achilles' problems forced other players to step  
up, and everything finally clicked Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	With Ewing concentrating on defense and rebounding, the Knicks  
whipped the ball around the perimeter and left Miami scrambling on 
defense. Sprewell and Allan Houston scored 22 points each and Larry 
Johnson had 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now everybody's getting a chance to shoot the ball,'' Sprewell  
said. ``It doesn't matter if it's Allen, Patrick, Larry or myself, 
we're going to go with the hot guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing scored nine points in 32 minutes, but led both teams with  
15 rebounds and blocked four shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key is not to think about him being in or him being out,''  
Houston said. ``I think he did a great job playing an all-around 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riley is fond of saying a playoff series hasn't really started  
until the home team has lost. That time is here, with the Heat 
needing to win at least once in New York to bring the series back 
to Miami for Game 5. 
</P>
<P>
	The Heat is 4-9 at Madison Square Garden since Riley left New  
York for South Florida. On the positive side: In each of the past 
two Miami-New York playoff meetings, the Game 1 loser has recovered 
to win the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to win two games in a row in this series,'' Van  
Gundy said. ``The team that wins has a tendency to come down in 
intensity, and the other team you know will come up in intensity. 
That's all the difference you need.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
