<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LA REALIDAD, Mexico (AP) -- The leader of the Zapatista rebels,  
Subcommandante Marcos, has returned to public view for the first 
time in more than two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcos appeared at a gathering of more than 2,000 cheering  
supporters late Saturday in La Realidad, a hamlet in a remote area 
of southern Chiapas state near the Guatemala border. With his 
trademark ski mask and pipe, Marcos delivered a speech railing 
against Mexico's political system. 
</P>
<P>
	The Zapatistas staged a brief uprising in January 1994 in the  
name of greater democracy and Indian rights. Almost immediately, 
Marcos captured the imagination of leftist intellectuals around the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	But the movement has withered in recent years. Marcos --  
identified by the government as university professor Rafael 
Sebastian Guillen -- disappeared from public view, although he 
continued to issue proclamations, presumably from the jungle. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- A group of 35 university  
students trapped in a cave for five days by flooding in southern 
Mexico were rescued Sunday, the Red Cross said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities had almost given up hope of finding the students  
alive. They had taken refuge a mile into the cave behind the 
waterfalls at Chorriadero, a tourist site in Chiapas state. 
</P>
<P>
	They were in good condition and were being taken to a hospital,  
the Red Cross said. 
</P>
<P>
	The students, from the National Polytecnical Institute in Mexico  
City, were exploring caves 35 miles from Tuxtla Gutierrez, the 
state capital, when heavy rains trapped them on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The mother of an American woman serving a life  
sentence for terrorism in a Peruvian prison received a special 
Mother's Day gift Sunday -- a hug from her daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time Rhoda Berenson, a physics professor at New  
York's Nassau Community College, had been allowed to touch her 
daughter Lori, 29, since Christmas. Prison officials normally keep 
them separate during visits except on special occasions. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Berenson, a former Massachusetts Institute of  
Technology student, was convicted on Jan. 11, 1996, for helping 
leftist Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement rebels plan a thwarted 
assault on Peru's Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Her parents say she is innocent and have campaigned to have her  
freed. U.S. officials have asked Peru to give Berenson an open, 
civilian trial, arguing that a closed military trial that found her 
guilty denied her due process. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Workers finished repairing a  
pipline that pumps tons of raw sewage into the ocean off Rio's most 
famous beaches, the local press reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Divers discovered leaks 12 days ago in the decrepit pipe along  
Rio de Janeiro's Ipanema beach. The pipe normally carries raw 
sewage from the city far out to sea. 
</P>
<P>
	While repairs were going on, tons of raw sewage were being  
dumped into the ocean along South Zone beaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents have held their noses as they passed darkened,  
foul-smelling waters along the beachfront hotels of fashionable 
Ipanema and its neighboring Copacabana and Leblon districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
