<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 16:41:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alomar To Be Reunited With Oriole's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- All eyes will be on right field and second base  
tomorrow night at Jacobs Field. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baltimore Orioles will make their first visit of the season,  
and that means you know who is back. 
</P>
<P>
	Albert Belle, once a Cleveland fan favorite, will be roaming  
right for the first time here since signing with the Baltimore 
Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle, who wore No. 8 and played left field for the Indians, now  
wears No. 88 and patrols right for the Orioles, but it's safe to 
say he won't go unnoticed by Cleveland fans, who have treated him 
rudely on his previous trips in. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-game series against Baltimore will also be Roberto  
Alomar's first game against his former teammates since the second 
baseman left the Orioles last November as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar spent three seasons with the Orioles (1996-98), making  
the All-Star team three times and helping the club get to the AL 
championship series twice. But last year, injuries resulted in his 
worst season since 1998 and he reportedly alienated himself from 
his teammates in the Baltimore clubhouse while playing out the 
final year of his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, he said he wouldn't treat the three-game set  
differently than any other. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just going to play my game and put it all out on the  
field,'' he said after the Indians' 5-4 win over Tampa Bay. ``I'm 
going to treat it like it's just another game, just like it's 
another series. I still have a lot of friends on the Orioles but 
there are no hard feelings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar, reunited this season with his brother, Indians catcher  
Sandy Alomar, has been everything Cleveland could have hoped for 
when the club signed him to a 4-year, $32 million contract during 
the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	After going 1-for-4 Sunday, he's batting .342 with five homers,  
19 RBIs and a team-leading 31 runs scored. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 16:12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Truck With Millions of Bees Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FALMOUTH, Maine (AP) -- A truck carrying millions of bees  
overturned on a highway ramp Sunday, leaving its cargo buzzing 
around the wreckage and closing down the roadway for nearly eight 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was one big swarm of bees over the truck, like a big  
black cloud,'' said Falmouth Patrolman Edward Roberge. 
</P>
<P>
	State police said the flatbed tractor trailer turned over on its  
side around 10 a.m. while heading north along a connection between 
the Maine Turnpike and Interstate 295 in this southern Maine town. 
Equipment was brought to the site around mid-day to lift the truck 
upright. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck was carrying between 400 and 450 hives, each home to  
between 40,000 and 45,000 bees, according to Falmouth Fire Chief 
James Robertson. He estimated there were about 20 million bees on 
the truck. 
</P>
<P>
	About five firefighters were stung, one as many as five times,  
but none were seriously hurt, Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters received tips from beekeepers who heard about the  
crash. They sprayed the dumped hives with water to calm the bees as 
they loaded the hives onto another truck in the late afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bees think it's raining and they won't leave the hives,''  
Roberston said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 16:51:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tornado Survivors Worship in Tent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. (AP) -- The bulldozers and chain saws were  
quiet as hundreds of worshipers gathered in a donated mud-covered 
tent on Sunday for church services, almost a week after a deadly 
tornado ripped through this rural community. 
</P>
<P>
	Half of a cement-block wall was all that stood at the Ridgecrest  
Baptist Church. ``God One, Tornado Zero'' was written on a worker's 
hard hat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if God took your home, but a tornado did, and God  
will rebuild your life,'' Pastor Tom Duckett told the standing room 
only crowd. ``I know that the church is the people. A building is 
just a building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bridge Creek, a collection of two churches, a school and 8,000  
scattered residents, doesn't even appear on a map. It was here that 
a tornado started a journey Monday evening that ended with at least 
41 dead statewide. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven of the victims died in Bridge Creek.  
</P>
<P>
	The number of people missing was lowered from four to one Sunday  
when two British tourists checked in with relatives in Australia 
and a local resident was taken off the missing list when his wife 
realized he was mistakenly on it. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Oklahoma City suburb of Moore, about 2,000 people  
gathered for a community-wide worship service. 
</P>
<P>
	``God will give us the strength to rebuild,'' Pastor Alan Cox of  
First Baptist Church told the Moore crowd, including Gov. Frank 
Keating and Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla. ``It's all right to cry. It's 
all right to hurt. It's all right to be confused. Hope will rebuild 
landmarks. Hope will outlive the broken hearts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Johns, president of Southwestern Insurance Information  
Service, said damage could top $1 billion once all the insurance 
claims have been filed. He said thousands of people have not filed 
claims yet. About 150,000 claims are expected, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers from the Federal Emergency Management Agency and 80  
college students from Missouri joined the worship in Bridge Creek. 
Duckett said members of all denominations from Catholics to Mormons 
have been helping at the church. 
</P>
<P>
	For awhile, the congregation will be tenting out, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We may be going to people's homes or in schools,'' he said.  
``We're not about a building. We're about the people inside.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 13:52:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Elway Wants NFL in L.A. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- John Elway is considering joining an effort  
to bring the NFL back to Los Angeles, the Los Angeles Times 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway, 38, retired a week ago after 16 seasons in the NFL,  
capping his record-setting career with two Super Bowl 
championships. His Los Angeles-based attorney, Marvin Demoff, told 
the Times that Elway wanted to stay involved in football. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's clear John's interests are to be involved in the  
day-to-day operation of a football team, whether it's Denver, Los 
Angeles or someplace else in the future,'' Demoff said. ``John made 
it known to me he does not want to be a passive celebrity investor; 
he's looking to make a contribution to a team on and off the 
field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billionaire developer Eli Broad and former Hollywood agent  
Michael Ovitz have separately contacted Broncos owner Pat Bowlen to 
ask for his blessing to approach Elway, the Times said. Broad and 
Ovitz head competing ownership groups vying for the NFL's 32nd 
franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway will meet with Broad on Tuesday in Los Angeles, but he has  
no plans to talk with Ovitz, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowlen offered Elway a chance to own a piece of the Broncos.  
However, Bowlen told Broad and Ovitz that it's unlikely he would be 
able to fulfill Elway's desire to work in a meaningful management 
position, according to the Times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990509.0100 </DOCNO>
