<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China Suspends Contacts With U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China suspended high-level military contacts with  
the United States on Monday following the bombing of its embassy in 
Yugoslavia. The official Xinhua News Agency said consultations with 
the United States on human rights, arms control, international 
security and preventing arms proliferation also were being 
postponed. Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao announced 
the decision to suspend the military and other contacts, Xinhua 
said. It did not say when they might resume. 

</P>
<P>
	China Protesters Decry NATO Attack  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Students held a third day of protests outside the  
U.S. and British embassies early Monday, trapping American 
diplomats inside their compound in demonstrations against NATO's 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia. Protesters marched 
along a police-guarded route that took them past the embassies. On 
Sunday, thousands thronged past the compounds, smashing windows at 
the U.S. mission with stones and splattering its walls with paint. 
NATO and the United States have said the embassy attack was 
accidental and have expressed deep regret. 

</P>
<P>
	CIA Error Blamed for Bombing Mixup  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A CIA error that was based on faulty  
information and then went undetected led to the mistaken NATO 
targeting and bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, a U.S. 
official said Sunday. The official said the intended target, the 
Yugoslav Federal Directorate of Supply and Procurement, was chosen 
by the CIA. Other organizations, including NATO, the U.S. European 
Command and the Pentagon's Joint Staff, approved it. The embassy is 
several hundred yards away from the Yugoslav government office. 
NATO and President Clinton offered further apologies Sunday for the 
bombing. 

</P>
<P>
	23 Die in Bus Crash in Louisiana  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Twenty-three people were killed when a  
chartered bus carrying members of a seniors casino club on a 
gambling excursion swerved off a highway, careening down an 
embankment. Eighteen more were hospitalized after the Sunday 
morning accident. Three were released after emergency room 
treatment. A witness and the bus driver said the bus swerved when 
it was cut off by another car. Mayor Marc Morial said it was the 
worst traffic accident in city history. 

</P>
<P>
	Skydiving Plane Crashes, Kills 6  
</P>
<P>
	CELINA, Ohio (AP) -- Five skydivers and the pilot of their plane  
died Sunday when the aircraft crashed into a field, authorities 
said. The accident happened about 5:30 p.m., south of Celina at 
Montezuma Lake Field Airport, according to the State Highway 
Patrol. Initial reports said the plane crashed into a field after 
experiencing engine trouble, the patrol said. The six occupants 
were dead at the scene. The Federal Aviation Administration is 
investigating. The National Transportation Safety Board is expected 
on the scene Monday, the patrol said. 

</P>
<P>
	'Wit' Wins Drama Desk Award  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Wit,'' which has already won the Pulitzer  
Prize, was named Sunday as outstanding new play of the 1998-99 
theater season by the Drama Desk. The Drama Desk, made up of 
theater writers, named ``Parade,'' a musical which had a short run 
at Lincoln Center, as outstanding new musical, in ceremonies held 
Sunday at LaGuardia High School of Music and Art and Performing 
Arts. Outstanding revival of a play was a tie between ``Death of a 
Salesman'' and ``The Iceman Cometh.'' 

</P>
