<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pharmacies Mix a Tastier Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Pharmacists are making cough syrup taste like  
pina coladas, antibiotics like coconut and liquid antacid like 
licorice sticks. 
</P>
<P>
	They're using flavorings to sweeten a bitter taste or mask  
strong medicine, making life easier for parents tired of battling 
with cranky, sick children with finicky palates. 
</P>
<P>
	Flavoring medicine is a growing business. One popular brand,  
called FLAVORx, was invented by a Washington, D.C., druggist for 
his own children. It is now available in 1,000 of the nation's 
76,000 pharmacies and that number is growing. Another drug company, 
Ascent Pediatrics of Wilmington, Mass., is developing ways to 
chemically neutralize bad tastes prior to adding flavors. 
</P>
<P>
	However, as the practice becomes more widespread, it's opening  
up a debate over safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Pharmacists consider the droplets they put in a bottle harmless,  
and can actually help because children are more likely to take the 
full dose. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we're doing is adding flavoring. We're not changing the  
dosage or the makeup,'' said Randy Dillon, a pharmacist at Petey 
Childers Prescriptions in Independence, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration hasn't received any reports  
that flavored drugs have injured anyone, said FDA pharmacist Tom 
McGinnis. 
</P>
<P>
	But, some medical experts are concerned about a lack of federal  
oversight. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patients are not being told that these products have never  
been tested,'' said John Perrin, professor of medicinal chemistry 
at the University of Florida, who worries that flavorings can 
dilute a drug or dangerously alter its chemical structure. ``They 
just assume that the pharmacist knows what he's doing and has 
scientific equipment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's potentially harmful any time that untested products are  
being routinely used in patients,'' said Larry Sasich, with the 
Public Citizen Health Research group, a Ralph Nader organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding flavors is part of a little-known pharmacy practice  
called compounding. Instead of just dispensing pills, the 
pharmacist customizes a drug, for instance creating a liquid form 
for patients who can't swallow pills. One decades-old practice is 
adding cherry flavor to children's medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1997 law is encouraging more compounding by restricting its  
regulation by the FDA. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington, D.C. pharmacist Kenneth Kramm invented FLAVORx seven  
years ago when his newborn daughter developed a seizure disorder, 
but kept spitting out her medication. So Kramm and his pharmacist 
father, Harold, began making flavor additives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was necessity,'' Kramm said. ``That's the way I guess some  
of the best things are invented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Word spread, and in October of 1995 the Kramms started marketing  
the additive to independent pharmacists. 
</P>
<P>
	FLAVORx comes in 42 flavors and costs $3 to $5 a bottle. In the  
past year, the regional drug store chains Giant Eagle of 
Pittsburgh, Giant Food of Washington, D.C., Marsh Supermarkets of 
Indiana, and Ukrop's in Richmond, Va. have begun selling it. At 
least one national chain, Rite Aid, is considering it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most popular things right now are children's  
antibiotics,'' said Randy Heiser, vice president of pharmacy for 
Giant Eagle. 
</P>
<P>
	FLAVORx is also used at several major hospitals, including San  
Diego Children's Hospital, The Cleveland Clinic and the Baptist 
Hospitals of San Antonio, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramm said he sold about $1 million worth last year. ``This year  
we're hoping to double that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	FLAVORx comes with a thick instruction book and a variety of  
flavor vials. There's cherry, chocolate, bubble gum, and grape 
along with pina colada, licorice, coconut, tangerine and 
butterscotch. 
</P>
<P>
	The recipes are fairly simple: 29 drops of grape and 12 drops of  
watermelon make a bottle of regular cough syrup taste like grape. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also available for picky pets. There is tuna flavor for  
cats, beef or liver for dogs and molasses for horses. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathy Peterson has been having drugs flavored at Kramm's Center  
Pharmacy for five years. Her children, Ross, 6, and Anne, 10, used 
to grimace and act like they were gagging whenever they took an 
antibiotic. 
</P>
<P>
	Flavored medicine doesn't taste like candy, she noted, but at  
least they no longer her fight her off. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes my life easier and I don't feel like I'm forcing  
anything on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Perrin, of the University of Florida, points out that  
antibiotics are developed with a specific acidity. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a stability problem. Chemicals will break down in the  
water, and will become ineffective or maybe even toxic,'' Perrin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He suspects that some illnesses that doctors thought were  
resistant to antibiotics are actually being treated by drugs 
rendered useless by flavoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Acidity and stability are ``my concern too'' said the FDA's  
McGinnis. The agency is writing new regulations on pharmacist 
compounding, but McGinnis said it won't intervene unless dangerous 
ingredients are used -- and flavorings are generally considered 
safe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kramms decided to order their own stability testing recently  
on flavored antibiotics, which ``have come out absolutely 
perfect,'' Kramm said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
