<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skydiving Plane Crashes, Kills 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CELINA, Ohio (AP) -- Five skydivers and a pilot died Sunday when  
their plane apparently lost power after takeoff and crashed in a 
soybean field, authorities and witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened about 6 p.m., south of Celina at Montezuma  
Lake Field Airport, according to the State Highway Patrol. The six 
occupants, five men and a woman, were dead at the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Dairy farmer Charles Schwieterman was taking a break from the  
afternoon milking when he heard the plane overhead, about a mile 
from the runway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought he was in trouble right away,'' said Schwieterman,  
61. ``He seemed like he wasn't getting anywhere. It seemed like he 
didn't have any power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The engine started sputtering, then ``clonked completely out,''  
Schwieterman said. He saw one skydiver jump out but the person's 
chute opened only partway, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The plane went into half a turn and went straight down head  
first,'' said Schwieterman, the first person to reach the downed 
airplane. He found at least three bodies lying outside the plane, 
which landed in a soybean field owned by a neighboring farmer. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwieterman said people skydive from the airport almost every  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims' names have been withheld pending the notification  
of their families. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration is investigating. The  
National Transportation Safety Board is expected on the scene 
Monday, the patrol said. 
</P>
<P>
	Celina is 27 miles southwest of Lima in west-central Ohio.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
